{[%evp 0,4,22,-17,20,-9,24] The starting position of this lecture arises after
} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 {The system with 2...Bb4 is very suitable for NID/QID
players. This line leads to similar middlegame patterns with Nimzo-Indian and
Queen's Indian Defences. Since this line is relatively less popular, the
theoretical overload is considerably less than in all other directions of the
English Opening. The vast majority of the arising middlegames are not based on
concrete theory. The typical plans and ideas that are discussed in the lecture
are more than sufficient for you to start playing this line.  There is also
another important practical benefit of playing this system. Since Black often
spoils White's structure with ...Bxc3, we immediately get an imbalance. In
return for the bishop pair, Black enjoys a superior pawn structure. Creating
such imbalances early in the game is one of the most efficient strategies when
we are fighting for a win. Depending on White's next move, we are going to get
a different type of position. You will find extensively annotated model games
covering the continuations 3.Qb3, 3.Qc2, 3.e4, 3.Nf3, and other moves that
allow the formation of doubled pawns in White's camp. In all the cases, Black
enjoys a solid position with chances to play for a win.} *

[Event "Tata Steel-A 80th"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee"]
[Date "2023.05.27"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Giri, Anish"]
[Black "Kramnik, Vladimir"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A13"]
[WhiteElo "2752"]
[BlackElo "2787"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "69"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Qb3 {This is one of the most principled systems against
the early ...Bb4. By attacking the bishop, White wants to obtain the bishop
pair without spoiling his own pawn structure. On the downside, if Black
refrains from ...Bxc3, the white queen is often misplaced on b3.  In my
opinion, the best reaction for Black is} ({In another game against Kramnik,
Giri tried} 3. Qc2 {In my opinion, Kramnik reacted very precisely again -} c5
4. a3 Bxc3 5. Qxc3 Qf6 $1 {This is the key move in order setup. If Whtie
refrains from exchanging the queens, we can proceed with ...Nc6, ...Nge7, and .
..0-0 followed by ...d7-d5 in the suitable moment.} 6. Qxf6 Nxf6 {[%cal Gb7b6,
Gd7d6,Gb8c6,Ge6e5] The endgame is completely safe for Black. After parting
with the dark-squared bishop, we need to put all our pawns on dark squares.} 7.
b4 b6 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Rb1 d6 10. e3 e5 $132 {[%cal Gc8f5] Black was doing fine
in the game ½-½ (54) Giri, A (2764)-Kramnik, V (2789) Leuven 2017. We are
ready to follow with ...Bf5. Under favourable circumstances, the idea of ...
e5-e4 followed by ...Ne5 is possible as well.}) 3... Ba5 {[%cal Bc7c5,Bb8c6,
Bg8e7,Be8g8,Bd7d5,Bd2d4,Bg8f6] This relatively less examined continuation is
nowadays the preferred choice of the top players. The fact that Kramnik plays
it on a regular basis speaks for itself. Ideally, Black would like to proceed
with ...c7-c5 followed by ...Nc6, ...Nge7, and ...d7-d5. In this case, it's
not clear what the queen is exactly doing on b3. Usually, we develop the
g8-knight to e7. If White, however, goes for an early d2-d4, then we should
develop the knight via f6! By studying the comments on the current game, you
will understand all the important subtleties.} 4. Nf3 {[%cal Bc7c5,Bg8e7,Bg8f6]
} c5 5. d4 {Giri goes for an early d2-d4 which seems to be the most principled
approach to the position.} ({In case of} 5. g3 {Black should play} Nc6 {
[%cal Bg8e7,Be8g8,Bd7d5]} 6. Bg2 Nge7 {This is the easiest solution. Now, at
any moment, White should reckon with the advance ...d7-d5.} ({Of course, the
alternative} 6... Nf6 {is playable as well. Nevertheless, after} 7. O-O O-O {
[%cal Bd7d5]} 8. d3 {I don't like the fact that the advance ...d7-d5 will be
very well met by cxd5 followed by Bg5, thus pinning the knight. Therefore,
Black should play} d6 9. h3 h6 10. e4 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gf3d2,Gf2f4] Even though
the position is objectively balanced, I don't like the fact that White's play
is pretty straightforward. He is going to proceed with simple moves such as
Be3 followed by Qd1, Nd2, and f2-f4. Of course, Black will also manage to
carry out the advance ...b7-b5. 0-1 (46) Krush,I (2429)-Abrahamyan,T (2344)
USA-ch (Women) Saint Louis 2021 (11)}) 7. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd7d5] White should
already reckon with the advance ...d7-d5.} 8. e3 {Preparing d2-d4 is the only
constructive plan for White in this position.} ({Another way to get the
advance d2-d4 is} 8. Rd1 {As a matter of fact, in this specific position, the
opposition along the d-file often works in Black's favour -} d5 9. d4 dxc4 10.
Qxc4 cxd4 11. Bf4 {White cannot take the d4-pawn immediately.} ({After} 11.
Nxd4 $2 {[%cal Bd8d1]} Bxc3 {[%cal Be6e5]} 12. bxc3 e5 $19 {Black is winning
because of the pin!}) 11... Bb6 12. Nb5 {This position was reached in the game
0-1 (37) Miles, A (2585)-Oll, L (2560) Sydney Cepacol 1991 (9).} ({A decent
alternative would have been} 12. Na4 {when the most straightforward line goes}
Nd5 13. Be5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bc7 15. Qxd4 Qf6 16. Nf3 Bd7 17. Nc5 Bc6 $11 {
with equality.}) {At this point, Black's most precise reaction would have been}
12... Ng6 {Since we cannot save the d4-pawn, we should try to get at least
something for it. In this case, Black will be relying on the bishop pair. The
play will continue} 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxf4 15. gxf4 Qe7 $132 {[%cal
Ge6e5] preparing the advance ...e6-e5. The bishop pair as well as the better
pawn structure provide Black with sufficient counterplay.}) 8... d5 {[%cal
Bd5d4] Of course. This advance is our first priority. Now, White should always
reckon with the advance ...d5-d4. In my opinion, the most natural answer is} 9.
d4 {when Black should take an important decision regarding the pawn structure.
In my opinion, the simplest is} Bxc3 {As we are heading for an IQP type of
position, exchanging minor pieces makes a lot of sense.} 10. Qxc3 ({Of course} 
10. bxc3 $2 {does not work in view of} Na5) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 {Quite
naturally, White avoids a position with an isolated pawn.} ({After} 11. exd4
dxc4 12. Qxc4 b6 13. Ne5 Na5 14. Qa4 Bb7 $132 {Black is doing fine. White
should keep finding dynamic resources in order to compensate for the static
weakness of his isolated pawn.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc6 13. Qc3 {[%cal Bf1d1,
Bb2b4,Bc1b2,Bc4d5] Once again, Black is at crossroads. With intends to
increase the pressure with Rd1 followed by b2-b3(b4), and Bb2. Black should go
for the right structure. The best move is} dxc4 ({In my opinion, after} 13...
d4 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Re1 {[%csl Bg2][%cal Bc1e3,Ba1d1,Bb2b4] White has a
considerable advantage in view of his powerful bishop pair and mobile
queenside majority. His next moves are going to be Be3 followed by Rad1.}) 14.
Qxc4 e5 $132 {[%csl Bf3,Bg2,Bh3,Bc1][%cal Bg2c6,Bc8e6,Bd8d7,Be6h3,Ba8c8,Bf8d8]
Activating the problematic light-squared bishop should be our priority.
Ideally, we would like to exchange the light-squared bishops. In such a
scenario, the tandem queen + knight will provide Black with a powerful play on
the light squares.  Winning a pawn with} 15. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 16. Qxc6 {is
completely wrong since after} Bh3 17. Re1 Rc8 18. Qe4 Qf6 $17 {[%csl Bc1][%cal
Bc8c4,Bf6f3,Bc4c2] Black develops tremendous initiative on the light squares.
Deflection ideas such as ...Rc4 and Rc2 are always in the air. For instance,
the natural} 19. Bd2 $2 {loses to} Rc4 $19 {when the rook cannot be taken in
view of ...Qf3.}) ({White can also play} 5. e3 {Since our opponent is
preparing a fast d2-d4, we should continue with} Nf6 6. d4 O-O $132 {[%cal
Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Black is doing perfectly fine. Later on, he will proceed with ...
b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7, and ...d7-d5. The queen is totally misplaced on b3.
As we will see in the main game, dxc5 is always well met by ...Na6.}) 5... Nf6
{This is always our reaction to ideas with fast d2-d4. Black is ready to
answer dxc5 with ...Na6 followed by ...Nxc5. Additionally, if White starts
protecting the c5-pawn, we can increase the pressure with ...Ne4. That's why
we develop the knight via a6 in case of fast d2-d4.} 6. dxc5 {This is the only
way to justify the previous play. Otherwise, Black will strike with ...d7-d5.}
({The Benoni structure arising after} 6. d5 exd5 7. cxd5 d6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal
Be8g8,Bf8e8,Ba7a6,Bb7b5,Bc8g4,Ba5e1] is obviously in Black's favour. In all
these positions, the queen is really misplaced on b3.}) 6... Na6 {[%cal Ba6c5]
This is our automatic reaction to dxc5. Since the queen has already
committed to b3, the move ...Nxc5 will come with a tempo.} 7. Be3 {[%csl Bf6]
Giri insists on keeping the c5-pawn which is the most principled continuation.}
({Of course, White can also play} 7. Bd2 {when after} Nxc5 8. Qc2 O-O {[%cal
Ba5c3,Bb7b6,Bc8b7,Ba8c8,Bd7d5] Black is doing fine. I have explained this type
of structure in my Nimzo-Indian camp where my suggestion was to meet 4.Qc2
with 4...c5 5.dxc5 0-0 with a similar play. In this concrete position, Black's
play is rather straightforward. He will proceed with ...b7-b6 followed by ...
Bb7, ...Rc8, and ...d7-d5.}) 7... Ne4 8. g3 $6 {This slow move allows Black to
achieve his dream position.} ({On the other hand, the more precise} 8. Bd4 {
fails to create any problems for Black. After} Naxc5 9. Qc2 {Black has a
pleasant choice. The simplest is} Bxc3+ ({If you are in an aggressive mood,
however, I can suggest the energetic} 9... b5 $5 10. cxb5 Bb7 11. e3 Rc8 $36 {
with a dangerous initiative. White should always reckon with the idea of ...
Nxc3 followed by ...Ne4. Using the position of the white queen is a common
theme in this Nimzo-Indian type of position. Black's play is practically
easier.}) 10. Bxc3 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Qf6 {Even though Black has a variety of good
options, I like this move inviting a favourable endgame after} 12. Qxf6 gxf6
$132 {The move ...gxf6 actually improves Black's structure since it increases
the central control and opens the g-file for the rook. Black will continue
with simple moves such as ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7, and ...Ke7. He has an
excellent play.}) 8... Naxc5 9. Qc2 Bxc3+ {An important move. We should take
the chance to spoil White's pawn structure.} 10. bxc3 b6 $15 {[%csl Bc3,Bc4]
[%cal Bc8b7,Ba8c8,Be8g8,Bd8e7,Bd7d6] First of all, we should prioritize the
development of the light-squared bishop. The idea is to proceed with ...Bb7
followed by ...Rc8. Black is already better since White does not have enough
dynamic resources to compensate for the doubled pawns.} 11. Bg2 Bb7 12. O-O O-O
13. Rfd1 Qe7 (13... Rc8 $15) 14. a4 d6 15. a5 f5 16. axb6 axb6 17. Nd4 Nf6 18.
Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Nb5 Rc8 21. Qa2 d5 22. Bg5 Rxc4 23. Qa8+ Kf7 24.
Ra1 Na5 25. Qb8 Rc6 26. Nd4 Rxc3 27. Qxb6 Nc4 28. Qb8 Nd7 29. Bxe7 Nxb8 30. Bb4
e5 31. Ra7+ Kg8 32. Bxc3 exd4 33. Bxd4 Nc6 34. Rxg7+ Kf8 35. Bf6 {1-0 White
wins.} 1-0

