{This game shows what might happen when White plays fast d2-d4 and neglects
the development.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Qb3 Ba5 4. d4 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Bb3][%cal
Bc7c5] Of course! Whenever we see fast d2-d4, we play ...Nf6 followed by ...
c7-c5. Since White spent a tempo on Qb3, Black wants to open the position and
get a dynamic play.} 5. Bg5 $6 {In my opinion, this move is dubious because
the kingside remains undeveloped. Therefore, it's not a surprise that after} c5
{White is the one who should maintain the balance (even though the computer
considers the position balanced).} 6. d5 $6 {This is already a serious
inaccuracy. Being behind in the development, White shouldn't go for this
dynamic Benoni structure.} ({As always,} 6. dxc5 {will be met by} Na6 {when
after} 7. Nf3 Nxc5 8. Qc2 {Black has} b5 $1 {which is a typical way of
exploiting the better development. Black wants to immediately open the c-file
and make use of the misplaced white queen.} ({It goes without saying that
there is nothing wrong with the natural} 8... Nce4 {when Black is perfectly
fine.}) 9. cxb5 Bb7 $17 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc5e4] Black will follow with ...Rc8, and
...Nce4. White is already in trouble.}) ({White should play a calm move such as
} 6. e3 {This position is not theoretical and Black has many good
continuations. One of them is} cxd4 7. exd4 h6 8. Bh4 O-O 9. Nf3 d5 $132 {
with a decent counterplay. The idea is to obtain a favourable version of IQP.})
({Another natural option would be} 6. Nf3 {In this case, the most ambitious
continuation is} h6 ({If you are not in a mood for dynamic play, you can
always play natural moves such as} 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6 $132 {followed by ...
0-0, ...h7-h6, and ...d7-d5. In all the cases, Black enjoys an excellent
counterplay since the white queen is misplaced on b3.}) 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4
$132 {This imbalanced position is practically easier for Black. He is ready to
proceed with ...Bxc3 followed by ...Nc6, and ...Qa5. At any moment, Black can
take the g3-bishop. White should play very energetically, in order to
compensate for his structural problems.}) 6... exd5 7. cxd5 O-O {[%cal Bd7d6]}
8. d6 $2 {This move is already a serious mistake. White's development in not
sufficient to sustain such a play. White should have tried to complete the
development as soon as possible. Of course, even in this case, Black would
have enjoyed a favourable Benoni type of position.} Nc6 {This move is natural
and good enough.} ({Starting with} 8... h6 {could have been even slightly more
precise. It's always useful to clarify the position of the g5-bishop. The game
might continue} 9. Bh4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 10. e3 b5 $17 {This pawn sacrifice
is perfectly justified by Black's superior development. White should now
reckon with ...c5-c4 followed by ...b5-b4. Obviously, Black's idea is to answer
} 11. Bxb5 {with} Rb8 {[%cal Bg7g5,Bf6e4,Bd8f6,Ba7a6,Bc8a6,Bc6b4] with a
winning initiative.}) 9. O-O-O Bxc3 $6 {This inaccuracy could have missed the
advantage.} ({Black should have played} 9... h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nd4 $17 {
with a fantastic initiative. For instance, after} 12. Qc4 b5 13. Qxc5 Bb6 14.
Qa3 a5 $19 {Black is already winning.}) 10. bxc3 $2 {After this mistake,
White's position is simply lost.} ({Obviously, White should have played} 10.
Qxc3 Ne4 11. Bxd8 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nxd8 13. e4 $13 {with an unclear play.}) 10...
b5 $19 {Black has a winning attack. Very soon he won the game.} 11. Nh3 c4 12.
Qxb5 Rb8 13. Qc5 Re8 14. e4 Ba6 15. Qa3 Qb6 16. Kc2 Nxe4 17. Be3 Qb5 18. Nf4
Nxf2 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

