{[%evp 0,22,28,-17,-7,-9,32,32,42,42,32,30,59,29,29,50,50,34,6,35,31,6,6,13,9]
This game covers 3.e4 which is one of White's most ambitious ways of playing
against 2...Bb4.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. e4 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gg1e2,Ga2a3] There
are two major ideas behind this move: 1) establish a powerful centre with d2-d4
2) continue with Nge2 followed by a2-a3, thus grabbing the bishop pair without
spoiling the pawn structure In my opinion, Black's most precise reaction is}
Ne7 {[%cal Bd7d5] when our immediate threat is ...d7-d5. Additionally, as we
are going to see in a while, Black is more than ready to play a position with
doubled pawns.} 4. d4 {This is the main continuation for White. Now, White is
ready to answer ...d7-d5 with cxd5 followed by e4-e5.} ({After} 4. Nf3 O-O 5.
d4 c5 6. d5 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. Bd3 e5 {we transpose into a position that is
examined later.}) ({The slow} 4. Nge2 {allows} d5 $132 {when Black immediately
starts fighting for the initiative.}) 4... c5 {In my opinion, this rare move
is the best way of handling the position. The idea is to provoke the advance
d4-d5, thus getting a blocked centre typical for the Huebner Variation in
Nimzo-Indian Defence.} 5. d5 {This is by far the most principled approach.} ({
White can also try} 5. a3 {when Black will react in a similar fashion -} Bxc3+
6. bxc3 O-O 7. Nf3 d6 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5] This move indicates our classical
strategy. After parting with the dark-squared bishop, Black wants to put his
central pawns on dark squares. Our next moves will be ...Nbc6 followed by ...
e6-e5. Let's see what happens when White tries to keep the central tension.} 8.
Bd3 Nbc6 9. O-O e5 10. h3 {A typical move in such positions. The idea is to
prevent Black from playing ...Bg4, thus putting pressure on d4. Black's main
strategy in such positions consists of provoking White to release the central
tension either by playing d4-d5 or dxe5. Therefore, Black will be trying to
put pressure on d4.} ({For instance, a good reaction to} 10. Be3 {would be}
exd4 11. cxd4 Bg4 $1 {This thematic move reminds me of the Yates Variation of the
Ruy Lopez. White can no longer keep the central tension.} 12. d5 {The most
logical choice.} ({Accepting the sacrifice with} 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Bxc5 {
does not promise much. After} b6 14. Be3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Ga8d8,
Ge7g6] Black enjoys fantastic compensation for the pawn. He will continue
with ...Rad8 and ...Ng6.}) 12... Ne5 13. Be2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 {A sad necessity.
White can not recapture with the bishop because the c4-pawn is hanging.} f5
$132 {Black has excellent counterplay in this position. In a practical game, I
would definitely take Black.}) 10... Ng6 {The knight is excellently placed on
this square. Besides supporting the e5-pawn, Black can also play ...Qf6
followed by ...Nf4. The following couple of moves are quite typical for this
structure.} 11. Ra2 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gc6a5] This move shows Black's other
typical idea in the pawn structure - attacking the c4-pawn by means of ...Ba6
and ...Na5. The following couple of moves are quite logical.} 12. Re1 h6 13.
Be3 Na5 14. a4 Ba6 15. Qe2 Re8 $132 {White remains without a constructive plan.
Black can also increase the pressure on c4 by means of ...Rac8. Sooner or
later, White will have to clarify the position in the centre.}) ({Keeping the
central tension with a move such as} 5. Nf3 {allows} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O $132 {
[%cal Gd7d5] followed by ...d7-d5 which is one of the main ideas behing ...Ne7.
Black can easily overtake the initiative in this position.}) ({The continuation
} 5. dxc5 {will be examined in the next example.}) 5... d6 ({Probably, I would
have started with} 5... Bxc3+ {when most likely we would transpose to the game.
}) 6. Bd3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 e5 {[%cal Bf7f5] This is the first critical position.
Compared to the Huebner Variation (suggested in my Nimzo-Indian camp), this
version is more favourable for Black. The reason is that here Black can
execute the thematic advance ...f7-f5 in one go while in the Huebner Variation
we need to prepare it. In this position, Black should apply the so-called
light square strategy. The reason is that he controls the light squares with
all his minor pieces while White's dark-squared bishop does not have any
influence on the light squares. Ideally, Black will exchange the light-squared
bishops as well as one pair of knights. In this scenario, the tandem queen +
knight will dominate White's completely useless dark-squared bishop.} 8. f4 $6
{This move is already an inaccuracy because after the exchange on f4, Black is
very well organized to fight for the e5-square.} ({The best move according to
the computer is} 8. h4 {gaining space on the kingside and discouraging any ...
Ng6 ideas. If possible, White will push the pawn all the way to h6. In a
practical game, however, not many people will play like this.} Nd7 {In my
opinion, Black is not forced to rush with the castle.} ({Wrong is} 8... f5 $6 {
in view of} 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qg5 {with h4-h5 to follow. White has a huge
advantage in this position.}) {A logical continuation of the game would be} 9.
h5 Qa5 10. Bd2 h6 11. Qg4 O-O 12. Qh4 f6 $132 {[%cal Ba5a4,Bd7b6,Bb6c4,Bf6f5]
Such a position would be quite typical for this line. Even though the computer
would give White some advantage, Black's play is practically easier. By means
of moves like ...Nb6 and ...Qa4 we can start attacking White's queenside pawns.
Also, under favourable circumstances, Black can play ...f6-f5. At the same
time, it's not easy to suggest a constructive plan for White.}) ({Most of your
opponents will play} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O {The following line shows how easily
Black can achieve his dream position -} h6 {Before proceeding with ...f7-f5,
it's important to take the g5-square under control. Otherwise, after the
exchange of the light-squared bishops, White will play Ng5-e6.} 10. a4 f5 11.
exf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 {[%csl Bc1,Bc3,Bc4,Ba4][%cal Bf8f1] Black is already
better in view of his superior pawn structure and the possibility to play on
the f-file. Let's go on a bit further -} 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Ne4 Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{[%cal Bf8f7,Ba8f8,Bf6g6,Bf5h4] Black managed to execute all the desirable
exchanges. He is now ready to apply his light square strategy. After doubling
the rooks along the f-file, he can proceed with ...Qg6 followed by ...Nh4. The
c1-bishop is completely useless.}) ({An interesting continuation is} 8. Ne2 {
This move is a kind of prophylaxis against ...f7-f5. Here, instead of the most
straightforward ...0-0 followed by ...f7-f5, Black should start with} Ng6 ({
White's idea becomes clear after} 8... O-O 9. O-O f5 $2 10. f4 $16 {This
position occurred in the game 1-0 (27) Mastrovasilis, A (2315)-Gasparian, T 
(2230) Yerevan 1997. Being behind in the development, Black is not ready to
play an open position.}) 9. O-O Nd7 {Having placed our knights on g6 and d7,
we are now ready to fight for the e5-square in case of f2-f4. After a move
such as} 10. Be3 {a very good idea is} h5 $1 {Now, we can say why Black
delayed castling for so long. Black is planning to gain even more space by
means of ...h5-h4.} 11. Qd2 h4 12. h3 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Ge8d8,Gd8c7] Black has
excellent play in this position. First of all, the king can occupy the
c7-square. This is the safest place for the king in this pawn structure. Later
on, Black can gradually build a kingside activity. For instance, the maneuver
..Nd7-f6-h5 always comes into consideration. Later on, Black can either
install a knight on f4 or strike with ...f7-f5.}) 8... exf4 9. Bxf4 Ng6 {
[%csl Be5]} 10. Bg3 {This position was reached in the game Erigaisi, Arjun
Kumar - Socko, B, 2021. Now, my choice would have been} Qe7 {[%csl Be5,Bd3,Bg3]
[%cal Bb8d7,Bd7e5]} 11. Nf3 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Gd7e5] followed by ...Nde5. Black
is already slightly better.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "Barcelona City 25th"]
[Site "Barcelona"]
