1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. e4 Ne7 4. d4 c5 5. dxc5 {This move is strategically
very risky. White accepts an inferior pawn structure in order to obtain the
bishop pair. Also, he relies on the fact that Black will have to invest some
time in order to regain the c5-pawn. With a precise play, however, Black can
even fight for an advantage in this line.} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Na6 {This is the
right way of handling this position. If Black manages to win the c5-pawn and
stabilize the position, he will be better. In order not to be left with all
the structural problems, White should play very energetically.} 7. Nf3 {
This developing move is the most natural continuation.} ({Another critical
direction is} 7. Qd4 O-O 8. Be3 {White shows his intention to keep the pawn as
long as possible. Such an approach, however, is quite risky because White has
serious lag in development. Even though Black cannot win the pawn back, he can
obtain an excellent compensation by means of} Qa5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Be7c6,Ba5c3,
Ba5a2]} 9. Rc1 Nc6 10. Qd6 b6 $1 {This is the key move. Besides eliminating
White's space advantage, Black brings his a8-rook into play and gets access to
the important c5-square.} 11. cxb6 axb6 {[%csl Bc5,Ba8][%cal Ba6c5,Ba8a2]} 12.
Nf3 Nc5 $132 {With all the weaknesses and lag in development, White should
play very precisely in order not to find himself in trouble.}) 7... Qa5 $1 {
This energetic move is Black's most precise continuation.} ({In the game,
Batsiashvili, N - Peralta, F, 2020, Black started with} 7... O-O $6 {when after
} 8. Be3 Qa5 9. Rc1 {White managed to consolidate. According to the computer,
Black does not have equality here.}) 8. Be3 Nxc5 9. Bxc5 {White has nothing
better than forcing transition into an endgame.} ({It's important that} 9. Qd4
{can be met by} b6 {The idea is that} 10. Qxg7 {is very well met by} Rg8 11.
Qf6 Nxe4 12. Qe5 Qxe5 13. Nxe5 d6 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black. White
does not have the slightest compensation for his structural problems.}) 9...
Qxc5 10. Qd4 Qxd4 11. cxd4 b6 12. Be2 Ba6 13. Nd2 Rc8 $132 {Even though this
endgame is roughly equal, I would definitely take Black since White's position
is overextended. Black can undermine the centre with ...d7-d5 and ...f7-f5.}
1/2-1/2

