{In this example, I will provide a brief repertoire against some systems
featuring doubled pawns. Since there is almost no theory, we will mainly rely
on typical plans and ideas.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Nf3 {This is the third
most popular move after 3.Qb3 and 3.e4. White prefers not to disclose his
intentions at this early stage of the game.} ({Another important direction is} 
3. g3 {White accepts a position with doubled pawns but tries to rule out
Black's plans based on ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7. Black has a variety of
good options but I will suggest a new concept that hasn't been seen in
practice -} Bxc3 {In most of the cases, we are more than happy to play a
position with doubled pawns in White's camp. White usually answers with} 4.
bxc3 ({Let's, however, take a look at the structure arising after} 4. dxc3 d6
5. Bg2 {The position on the diagram is a kind of Rossolimo with colours
reversed. There are, however, some important differences. Black's knights are
still on their initial positions. Therefore, unlike in Rossolimo, Black will
often play ...f7-f5 in one go. Another very important detail is that Black
should go for a fast ...a7-a5 idea. The obvious intention is to keep gaining
space with ...a5-a4. If White plays a2-a4 in response, then the b8-knight will
be immediately transferred to c5. Let's take a look at some sample lines that
I have created.} a5 $1 {A very important move in our strategy. By threatening .
..a5-a4, Black wants to provoke the advance a2-a4, so that his knight could be
extremely powerful on c5.} 6. Nf3 {White has many other options but nothing
would dramatically change the character of the position. By choosing the move
Nf3, I would like to explain how to handle the structure when White ignores
the threat of ...a5-a4.} ({Obviously, we should also consider} 6. a4 {In this
case, Black can play} Nf6 ({Structurally speaking, the move} 6... f5 {is very
advantageous for Black. Especially, if we manage to proceed with ...Nf6
followed by ...e6-e5, and ...Na6, our position will be clearly superior. The
problem here is that our insufficient development allows White to handle the
position in a dynamic way -} 7. c5 $1 {This break is often annoying in such
positions. With a pawn on f5, Black is especially vulnerable to this advance.
After} dxc5 8. Qb3 $44 {White has an obvious compensation but the position
remains playable. If you are ambitious enough, you can investigate this
position even further.}) ({Black can also start with} 6... Na6 {taking the
c5-square under control and in response to} 7. Nf3 {opt for} f5 {Now as c4-c5
is not on the table Black is ready to proceed with ...Nf6 followed by ...e6-e5.
Unfortunately, White has} 8. e4 $1 {which appears to be very strong. The game
might continue} fxe4 9. Ng5 d5 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qe2 $16 {White has a huge
advantage in this position. He is ready to open the position with f2-f3 when
Black will be in a big trouble.}) 7. Nf3 Na6 $1 {This is a key move in our
strategy. Almost always, the knight will be heading for the c5-square. With
the inclusion of the moves ...a7-a5 and a2-a4, the knight will be especially
strong on this square. The following couple of moves are quite logical and
thematic for this pawn structure -} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 e5 10. e4 Be6 11. b3 Nc5
12. Nd2 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gf1e3] This is a typical move. The knight is
heading for the d5-square. Therefore, White is planning to proceed with Re1
followed by the maneuver Nd2-f1-e3-d5. On the other hand, Black's strategy
remains unchanged. He wants to exchange the light-squared bishops as well as a
pair of knights. Afterward, he will start playing on the light squares.
Another very important idea is to carry out the break ...f7-f5. A logical move
for Black would be} Qd7 {[%cal Ge6h3] intending ...Bh3.} 13. Re1 Bh3 14. Nf1 {
After playing e2-e4, White is usually ready to exchange the bishops.} ({
In the case of} 14. Bh1 {we can play this typical} Kh8 {[%cal Gf6g8,Gf7f5]
preparing ...Ng8 followed by ...f7-f5. After} 15. Nf1 Ng8 16. Ne3 Ne7 $132 {
[%cal Gb7b6,Ga8e8,Gf7f5] Black enjoys decent counterplay. First of all, we
need to remove all our pieces from the long diagonal by means of ...b7-b6 and .
..Rae8. Afterward, the advance ...f7-f5 is on the agenda.}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2
Kh8 {[%cal Gf6g8,Gf7f5] with ...Ng8 and ...f7-f5 to follow. Black has an
excellent play in this position.}) 6... a4 {Even though we can first develop
the kingside, I like to play this move as soon as possible. Let's now suppose
that White plays just like after the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5
-} 7. O-O Nf6 8. Qc2 O-O 9. e4 Nbd7 10. Re1 e5 11. Nd2 Nc5 12. Nf1 Be6 13. Ne3
{This time, the white knight is tied to the defence of the c4-pawn. Therefore,
Black enjoys even more freedom. He can start playing on the kingside by means
of} h5 {when it's very difficult for White to meet the idea of ...h5-h4.} ({
After having pushed our pawn all the way to a4, we can also consider} 13... c6
14. f3 b5 15. cxb5 cxb5 {[%csl Ra1,Ra2,Ga4,Gb5] with a very typical position.
The white rook is tied to the defence of the a2-pawn.}) 14. h3 {This move
allows Black to further weaken White's kingside.} ({Ignoring ...h5-h4 is not
better. For instance, after} 14. Rb1 h4 15. b4 axb3 16. axb3 g6 $15 {[%cal
Gg8g7,Gf8h8] Black has decent attacking chances. He is ready to proceed with ..
.Kg7 followed by ...Rh8.}) 14... h4 15. g4 Nh7 {[%cal Gh7g5] with ...Ng5 and
eventually ...Qf6 to follow. Black is already slightly better.}) 4... b6 $1 {
I was surprised to see that the move ...b7-b6 works even in this case. Also,
this move is advocated by the computer!} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e4 d6 {This position is
totally unexplored. Hence, it makes no sense to study concrete variations. We
should rather think in concepts. For instance, White should decide whether to
play d2-d3 or d2-d4. You just need to know two rules of thumb: 1) When White
plays d2-d3, you play ...Bb7, ...Qd7, followed by ...Nge7, and ...0-0-0. Later
on, we initiate active actions on the kingside. 2) When White plays d2-d4, we
castle short and start putting pressure on c4. Let's briefly take a look at
two sample lines:} 7. d4 {After seeing this move, we know that we should focus
on the c4-pawn.} ({The alternative direction is} 7. d3 Bb7 8. Nf3 Qd7 9. O-O
Nge7 $132 {[%cal Ge8c8] with ...0-0-0 to follow. The king is completely safe
on the queenside and we can start advancing the kingside pawns.}) 7... Nge7 8.
Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Ba6 10. Nd2 Na5 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gc7c5] The pressure on c4 is
rather annoying. Black's play is practically easier. In the next couple of
moves, he will play ...c7-c5 followed by ...Qd7, and ...Rc8.}) 3... Bxc3 4.
bxc3 {This is the most ambitious recapture. White increases the central
control and opens the b-file for the rook. I should say, however, that Black's
plan remains almost unchanged in both cases.} ({Let's also take a look at} 4.
dxc3 {Just like after 4.bxc3, we should start with} f5 {It's very profitable
that we can play this move at once, without any preparations. It's very
important to answer the move} 5. g3 {[%cal Bc8b7] with} b6 {In this case, we
make sure that} 6. Bg2 {is always safely met with} Bb7 {After} 7. O-O Nf6 {
[%cal Be8g8,Bd7d6,Be6e5,Bb8d7,Bd8e8,Be8h5,Bf5f4] We can say that Black is
already practically better. After castling, he will follow with simple moves
such as ...d7-d6 followed by ...e6-e5, and ...Nbd7. Later on, Black can
develop a kingside attack with ...Qe8-h5 followed by ...f5-f4. At the same
time, White's plan remains unclear. Let's briefly take a look at one example:}
8. Bg5 O-O 9. Qd2 Qe8 10. Bxf6 {In principle, this exchange is correct since
the dark-squared bishop is completely useless in this pawn structure. On the
other hand, the black rook can now easily join the attack.} Rxf6 11. Rad1 d6
$15 {[%cal Bb8d7,Be6e5,Be8h5,Ba8f8,Bf5f4,Bf6h6] Black has excellent attacking
prospects. He can use the attacking scheme that I mentioned above. 0-1 (42)
Greco, U-Cherniaev, A (2509) Nice op 9th 2002 (6)}) 4... f5 {Once again, we
should start with this move.} 5. g3 b6 {Never forget to answer g2-g3 with ...
b7-b6!} 6. Bg2 Bb7 {[%csl Bb7,Bg2,Bc1][%cal Bg8f6,Be8g8,Bd7d6,Be6e5,Bb8d7,
Bd8e8,Be8h5] Black is ready to employ the attacking scheme we are familiar
with - after completing the development and playing ...e6-e5, he will consider
bringing the queen to h5. Also, we shouldn't forget the favourable exchanges.
Black wants to apply a light square strategy after exchanging the
light-squared bishops as well as a pair of knights. In the resulting positions,
the c1-bishop will be completely useless.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3 O-O {This position
has been reached in several practical games. Black is already better. Now, we
shall just take a look at some of the examples.} 9. Re1 {With this move, White
indicates his intention to play e2-e4 at some point. It goes without saying
that this idea is not dangerous for Black.} ({Pointless is} 9. Ba3 {[%csl Ba3]
when after} d6 {[%cal Bd3d4,Bc4c5] the a3-bishop is misplaced. Had the white
pawn been on d4, White could have considered the advance c4-c5.} 10. Re1 ({
Harmless is} 10. Nd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qd7 12. Qb3 {[%csl Bc3,Bc4][%cal Bc7c5]
This position was reached in the game Malicka, M - Borowy, C, 2015. White is
hoping to get some dynamic play with c4-c5. In this case, the simplest
solution would be} c5 {Fixing the doubled pawns is always useful. In this way,
we rule out any dynamic ideas that White might have at his disposal. After} 13.
Nf3 Nc6 14. Rae1 e5 $17 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Ba8e8,Bf5f4,Bc6d8,Bd8f7] Black has a
huge advantage. After ...Rae8, he can bring the c6-knight to the kingside and
prepare ...f5-f4. White does not have constructive ideas here.}) 10... Qe8 11.
Qb3 Nbd7 ({Another very good move that I would have played is} 11... c5 {
fixing the doubled pawns.}) 12. d4 Rb8 {This move is a prophylaxis against the
advance c4-c5.} 13. Rad1 Kh8 14. d5 {White intends to fight for the e6-square
by means of Ng5. Structurally speaking, however, the advance d4-d5 is terrible.
White's structure loses it's flexibility and Black gets access to the
c5-square.} e5 {This move does not spoil the advantage.} ({Starting with} 14...
Nc5 $17 {would have been even more precise. Before everything else, Black
takes the e6-square under control.}) 15. Ng5 {Now, this move gives at least
some chances to White. Even though there are some mistakes, the remaining part
of the game is instructive.} Nc5 16. Qc2 Qh5 17. h4 h6 18. Bf3 Qg6 19. Bxc5
hxg5 20. hxg5 Qxg5 21. Be3 f4 22. Bc1 Bc8 23. Kg2 Bf5 24. e4 fxe3 25. Qe2 e4
26. Rh1+ Kg8 27. Bh5 Nxh5 {0-1 Balogh,L (1930)-Leszko,B (2081) Eger Agria op
40th 2016 (6)}) ({More logical is to play Ba3 after the inclusion of the moves
} 9. a4 a5 10. Ba3 {Let's take a look at one instructive example -} d6 11. d4
Nbd7 12. d5 {Once again, White starts fighting for the e6-square. As shown
in this example, very often the knight is doing nothing on e6. Black can simply
exchange it. As a result, White will remain with all his structural problems.}
e5 13. Ng5 Qe7 14. Ne6 Rfc8 {[%cal Gd7f8] At any moment, Black can follow with
...Nf8. Actually, the e6-knight is rather useless, since it's not supported by
the rest of the army.} 15. Qb3 Rab8 $1 {An important prophylactic move against
the advance c4-c5.} 16. Rad1 Ba6 ({Black could have played} 16... Nf8 {
immediately.}) 17. Qa2 Nf8 18. Nxf8 Rxf8 $19 {Black is strategically winning.
Now, when the queenside is completely fixed, Black's kingside attack will be
devastating. I include the rest of the game without providing comments.} 19.
Bc1 Nd7 20. f3 Rbe8 21. Be3 Qf7 22. Rfe1 Qh5 23. Bf2 Rf6 24. e4 Ref8 25. exf5
Qxf5 26. Re4 g5 27. g4 Qg6 28. Qe2 Rf4 29. Rxf4 Rxf4 {0-1 Enigl,K (2027)
-Brosig,B (2127) Landesliga Sued 1112 Bayern 2011 (7.5)}) 9... Qe7 10. a4 a5 {
This move is our thematic reaction to a2-a4. At some point, the a4-pawn might
become a weakness.} 11. Qb3 d6 {[%cal Bb8d7,Bg8h8,Be6e5] Black is ready to
follow with his thematic moves - ...Nbd7, ...Kh8, and ...e6-e5.} {This advance
is White's only constructive idea. As we will see, however, Black is in very
decent shape.} 12. e4 fxe4 13. Ng5 h6 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Rxe4 Nd7
$15 {[%csl Bc1,Bd7,Be7][%cal Bf8f2] This position was reached in the game ½- 
(26) ½ Szeles,K (2230)-Soponyai,A (2038) HUN-chT2 Szechenyi 1011 Hungary 2010
(2.3). Black is already better since the tandem queen and knight has
tremendous potential on the light squares. As always, the white bishop is
doing nothing. Also, Black's play along the f-file is rather annoying.} *

