{[%evp 0,52,29,32,33,-5,27,27,27,26,18,23,23,15,45,46,46,33,22,8,11,23,16,-2,8,
-1,3,-5,3,-114,-90,-90,-75,-309,-201,-194,-194,-348,-332,-225,-270,-270,-224,
-383,-337,-380,-382,-519,-508,-510,-510,-666,-671,-673,-658] Now, we shall
take a look at some examples in which White puts his bishop on d3.} 1. d4 ({
Again, our move order is going to be different -} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Nf3
Bxc3 4. bxc3 f5 5. d4 Nf6 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 {when we transpose to the game.})
1... e6 2. c4 b6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Bb7 6. Nf3 f5 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O
O-O {In my opinion, this setup is much more challenging than the plans with
g2-g3 followed by Bg2. White has better control of the e4-square and often
tries to organize the advance e3-e4 by means of Nd2 followed by f2-f3. As we
will see, however, this plan is not challenging at all. The most dangerous
approach is based on Ba3 followed by c4-c5. Therefore, Black often fixes
White's queenside with the move ...c7-c5.} 9. Qc2 {Played with the idea of
reinforcing the control of the e4-square. This move, however, has a lot of
drawbacks. For instance, Black can either spoil the kingside structure with ...
Bxf3 or exchange the light-squared bishops via e4. Vallejo played} Qe8 {
[%cal Gd7d6,Gb8d7,Ge8h5] planning to proceed with ...d7-d6, ...Nbd7, and the
bring the queen to h5.} (9... Be4 $5) (9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qe8 $132) 10. Nd2 d6
11. f3 Nbd7 12. Re1 {White keeps preparing the advance ...e3-e4. Also, the
f1-square is now available for the knight.} ({The thematic reaction to} 12. e4
{is} fxe4 13. fxe4 e5 14. a4 a5 $15 {[%cal Ge8g6,Ga8e8] Due to the indirect
pressure on the e4-pawn, White cannot move the d2-knight. Black is always
happy to provoke his opponent to release the central tension with either dxe5
or d4-d5. He is ready to increase the pressure on e4 by playing ...Qg6
followed by ...Rae8. Black is already slightly better.}) 12... Qh5 13. Nf1 Rae8
{Black is gradually building his kingside play. Preparing the advance ...e6-e5
is the main idea in the position.} 14. e4 {Now or never!} fxe4 15. fxe4 e5 {
Vallejo answers in a thematic way.} ({According to the computer, slightly more
precise would have been} 15... Ng4 {[%cal Gf8f1]} 16. h3 Nf2 17. Re3 Nxd3 18.
Qxd3 Qg6 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black. White cannot withstand the
pressure on e4 for too long.}) 16. Ng3 $2 {A mistake in a very difficult
position.} ({A bit more tenacious would have been} 16. c5 {Nevertheless, after}
exd4 17. cxd6 Ne5 $17 {Black enjoys an overwhelming initiative.}) 16... Qh4 $19
{[%cal Gf6g4] Black is winning since there is no defence against ...Ng4.} 17.
Be3 Ng4 18. Nf1 Rxf1+ 19. Kxf1 Rf8+ 20. Ke2 Qxh2 21. Kd1 Nxe3+ 22. Rxe3 exd4
23. cxd4 Qg1+ 24. Re1 Qxd4 25. Rc1 Ne5 26. Qc3 Qxd3+ {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

