{[#] This game shows how to handle the position when White wants to carry out
the advance e3-e4 without playing f2-f3.} {In the position on the diagram,
White played the direct} 12. e4 {Instead of building a strong pawn centre, he
wants to put pressure on e6.} fxe4 13. Nxe4 {This position occurred in the
game Manush, S - Ostrovskiy, A, 2020. At this point, the right approach would
have been} Nxe4 ({Instead, Black played} 13... e5 $2 {when after} 14. Ng5 $1
$16 {White could have obtained an obvious advantage.}) 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Qxe4
e5 $132 {Black has excellent counterplay in this position in view of his
better pawn structure and domination on the light squares. White should keep
playing energetically in order to maintain the balance.} 0-1

