{[%evp 0,28,27,3,33,25,25,36,36,36,36,23,23,14,6,14,22,22,36,30,30,22,26,32,20,
36,32,24,25,8,4] In this theoretical file prepared by GM Mihail Marin, you
will find how to handle White's most ambitious ways of handling the structure
with doubled pawns.} 1. c4 b6 {This move order is due to the fact that the
line is analyzed in Marin's database dedicated to the Owen Defence.} ({Our
move order will be} 1... e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. d4 Bxc3+ 4. bxc3 f5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. e3
O-O 7. Bd3 b6 8. O-O Bb7 {reaching the position from the main line.}) 2. d4 Bb7
3. Nc3 e6 4. Nf3 f5 5. e3 Nf6 6. Bd3 Bb4 7. O-O {This is a dynamic approach.
White does not waste time with Bd2, hoping that his massive centre will offer
him chances to take over the initiative.} Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Ba3 {One of the
possible plans.} (9. Ne1 {[%cal Bf2f3]} c5 {[%csl Bc3,Bc4]} 10. f3 Nc6 (10...
Qe7 11. Nc2 d6 12. Qe2 Nc6 13. e4 {Hernandez Onna,R (2435)-Piasetski,L (2395)
Alicante 1977 (1/2-1/2, 57)} fxe4 14. fxe4 Nd7 15. Be3 Rxf1+ 16. Rxf1 Rf8) 11.
Bb2 Qe7 {[%cal Bd7d6,Be6e5,Bg7g6]} 12. Qe2 d6 13. g3 Rae8 14. Ng2 g6 15. Qd2
Na5 16. Rae1 Qc7 17. Qe2 e5 18. e4 exd4 19. cxd4 cxd4 20. Bxd4 Nc6 21. Bxf6
Rxf6 22. Qb2 Ne5 23. exf5 {Sreeshwan, M (2244)-Marin, M (2539) Roquetas de Mar
2019 (1/2-1/2, 61)} Rff8 $15) (9. Nd2 d6 10. f3 c5 11. Qe2 (11. e4 fxe4 12.
fxe4 Nc6 13. Nf3 e5 14. d5 Ne7 {[%cal Gb7c8]}) 11... Nc6 {Nakauchi,G (2191)
-Cheng, B (2377) Cammeray 2013 (0-1, 53)}) (9. a4 Nc6 10. Ba3 (10. Nd2 d6 11.
Nb3 Ne7 12. a5 c5 {Rubinstein,A-Maroczy,G Teplitz Schoenau 1922 (1-0, 33)
White has spent too much time on his plan and the knight stands badly on b3.
Black does not have any special problems.}) 10... d6 (10... Re8 11. Nd2 d6) 11.
d5 exd5 (11... Na5 12. Ng5) 12. cxd5 Ne7 13. c4 $16 {Dmitrienko,A (2216)-Lysyj,
I (2490) Tomsk 2003 (35, 0-1)}) (9. c5 Ne4 10. cxb6 axb6 11. c4 d6 (11... Nc3
12. Qe1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qg5+ 14. Kh1 Qh5 15. Rg1 Qxf3+ 16. Rg2 Rf6 17. Kg1 Ne4
18. Be2 Qh3 19. f3 Nd6 20. c5 Ne8 21. cxb6 cxb6 22. d5 $13) (11... Rf6 $132 12.
Nd2 Rh6 13. Nxe4 Qh4 14. h3 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 fxe4 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 12. Bb2 Nd7
13. Nd2 e5 14. Bxe4 fxe4 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 dxe5 17. c5 b5 18. Nb3 (18.
Qb3+ Qd5 19. Qb2 Bc6) 18... Bd5 19. Qc2 c6 $15 {0-1 (30) Anagnostopoulos, K 
(2117) -Nabaty,T (2604) Anogia 2015}) 9... Re8 $5 {[%cal Bf3d2,Bd7d6,Bd4d5,
Bf3d4] My favourite move, maintaining the structural flexibility.} (9... d6 {
is not a bad move, but it exposes Black to two different pawn breaks.} 10. d5 {
The thematical pawn break after ...d7-d6, but with the bishop relatively
passive on a3, the consequences are not that clear. It was better to keep the
tension with:} (10. c5 {, when Black could hold approximate equality with} dxc5
11. dxc5 Re8 {[%cal Gb8d7] For instance:} 12. Bb5 Bc6 13. c4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1
bxc5 15. Bxc5 a6 16. Bxc6 Nxc6) 10... Qe8 $5 $146 {, for instance:} (10... exd5
$6 {Capturing too early on d5 unblocks the c3-pawn, helping the a3-bishop to
join the fight with c3-c4 and Bb2.} 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. Bxf5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (38)
Navin, K (2307) -Sandipan, C (2555) Jammu 2018}) 11. dxe6 (11. Nd4 exd5 {Now
this is forced, but Black is ready to exchange the other white bishop:} 12.
cxd5 Bxd5 13. Nxf5 Nbd7 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd7e5]} 14. c4 Be4 15. Rc1 Qe5 16.
Bxe4 Qxe4 17. Ng3 Qe5 $132) (11. Re1 g6 $5 12. e4 fxe4 13. Bxe4 Nxe4 14. Rxe4
e5 15. Bc1 Na6 {[%cal Gb7c8]}) 11... g6 12. c5 $5 (12. Nd4 Na6) 12... dxc5 13.
Bb2 Nc6 (13... Qxe6 14. Ng5 Qe7 15. Qb3+) 14. c4 (14. Bc4 Na5) 14... Rd8 {
Due to Black's activity, it is not easy for White to create threats along the
long dark diagonal.}) 10. Nd2 (10. Rb1 Be4) (10. c5 bxc5 11. Bxc5 (11. dxc5 Be4
12. Be2 Nc6) 11... Ne4 12. Rc1 Nxc5 13. dxc5 {[%cal Gd3f5,Gd1b3]} Bc6 $5 {
[%cal Gd8e7]} (13... Na6 14. c6 dxc6 15. Bc4 Nc5) 14. Nd4 Qe7 15. Qb3 g6 16.
Qa3 a5 $13) (10. Rc1 d6 11. c5 dxc5 12. dxc5 Nbd7 $5) 10... c5 (10... d6 $5 {
[%cal Bc7c5,Bd8d7,Bb8c6,Be6e5] works, too.}) 11. dxc5 Qc7 12. f3 (12. cxb6 axb6
13. Bb4 Ng4 $36) 12... Na6 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Nb3 Nc5 $44 {White's numerous
