{[%evp 0,78,26,0,0,-20,-17,-24,2,-10,-12,-16,36,30,19,16,27,19,11,3,27,22,30,
32,22,26,23,23,16,16,18,1,0,-6,4,-6,1,1,14,-15,11,1,-12,4,4,-10,24,13,26,24,30,
34,43,31,43,0,-134,-109,-165,-138,-147,-152,-156,-156,-161,-173,-170,-225,-170,
-151,-178,-186,-186,-186,-144,-162,-194,-188,-188,-186,-184] This high-profile
game deals with White's most principled (and objectively best) approach
against Black's setup. It's not a surprise that Nepomniachtchi went for it in
his World Championship match against Magnus Carlsen.} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2
d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Bc5 {[%csl Bf6][%cal Bg8f6,Be6e5,Be5e4,Bf6d7,Bd7c5,Ba7a5,
Ba8a6,Ba6g6] Don't forget that the bishop will occupy the c5-square only
temporarily. The idea is to support the centre until Black completes the
development. In the long run, the c5-square is reserved for the knight.} 6. d3
Nf6 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Bd2b3,Be2e3] This continuation is White's best choice
according to the computer. White wants to destroy Black's space advantage with
Nb3 followed by e2-e3.} a5 {[%cal Bd2b3,Ba5a4] In my opinion, this typical
move is Black's most precise reaction. Besides gaining space on the queenside,
Black is already ready to disturb the b3-knight by means of the advance ...
a5-a4.} 8. Nb3 Be7 9. e3 {This is the only logical follow-up after Nb3.
Otherwise, the b3-knight is going to be quite misplaced.} ({The following
cooperative line shows Black's dream scenario in such structures -} 9. h3 O-O
10. Re1 a4 11. Nbd2 Nd7 {[%csl Bc5] We can see the main advantage of this pawn
structure. Since there is no pawn on c5, this square is available for the
knight.} 12. Ne4 f5 13. Ned2 Nc5 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Be6e5,Be5e4] Black is ready
to carry out the central expansion by means of ...e6-e5-e4. This line shows
how easy for Black are such positions. White should play very energetically in
order not to find himself in a huge trouble.}) 9... dxe3 10. Bxe3 {[%cal Bd3d4,
Bh2h3,Bd1e2,Bf1d1,Ba1c1,Bd4d5] We have reached an important position. If left
undisturbed, White will put annoying pressure on Black's position by taking
a firm grip on the centre. He will follow with simple moves such as Qe2, Rfd1,
Rac1, and d3-d4. Black should play energetically in order not to find himself
in a position without counterplay.  The most precise reaction seems to be} Ng4
{[%cal Bg4e3,Ba5a4] By chasing the bishop away, Black actually fights for the
important d4-square. As usual, the advance ...a5-a4 is always an option.} 11.
Bc5 {Of course, White cannot surrender the bishop pair for free.} {The
following couple of moves are quite logical -} O-O 12. d4 a4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14.
Nc5 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Ba4a3,Be6e5,Bf8d8] So far, White has been playing the
best moves according to the computer. His hopes are based on the annoying
Catalan pressure and good central control. On the other hand, White's position
tends to be overextended. Therefore, in practical terms, Black's play seems
easier. We can attack the vulnerable d4-pawn either by ...Rd8 or ...e6-e5.
Carlsen started with} a3 {[%cal Bf8d8] which in my opinion is a slight
inaccuracy since White can play b2-b3 in one go.} ({The straightforward} 14...
e5 {[%cal Bf8d8] would have been better. Black wants to proceed with ...Rd8.
The critical line goes} 15. Re1 Rd8 16. b4 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Bd4d5] Protecting
the knight and planning d4-d5. It's very difficult for a human to find this
precise move. Nevertheless, the sequence} axb3 17. Nxb3 e4 18. Nfd2 f5 19. f3
Nf6 20. fxe4 Nxd4 21. exf5 Qf8 22. Nxd4 Rxd4 $132 {[%csl Bg1][%cal Bc8f5,Bf6g4,
Bf8c5,Ba8d8] leads to a position in which Black enjoys fantastic counterplay.
His position is practically better in view of the vulnerable white king.}) 15.
bxa3 {After this move the game is balanced.} ({After the precise} 15. b4 $1
Nxb4 16. Rb1 b6 17. Rxb4 bxc5 18. Rb5 $14 {White could have relied on a small
advantage.}) 15... Rd8 $132 {Black has enough counterplay in this position.
Later on, Carlsen even managed to win this final game and defend his title.}
16. Nb3 Nf6 17. Re1 Qxa3 18. Qe2 h6 19. h4 Bd7 20. Ne5 Be8 21. Qe3 Qb4 22. Reb1
Nxe5 23. dxe5 Ng4 24. Qe1 Qxe1+ 25. Rxe1 h5 26. Bxb7 Ra4 27. c5 c6 28. f3 Nh6
29. Re4 Ra7 30. Rb4 Rb8 31. a4 Raxb7 32. Rb6 Rxb6 33. cxb6 Rxb6 34. Nc5 Nf5 35.
a5 Rb8 36. a6 Nxg3 37. Na4 c5 38. a7 Rd8 39. Nxc5 Ra8 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

