{This game shows what happens when ...dxe3 is answered with fxe3.} 1. c4 e6 2.
g3 d5 3. Bg2 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Bc5 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nbd2 O-O {In my opinion,
this move order is slightly less precise. Nevertheless, it's completely
playable.} ({As we have seen from the previous example, the scientific
approach is} 7... a5 8. Nb3 Be7 9. e3 dxe3 10. Bxe3 Ng4 {reaching the game
Nepomniactchi - Carlsen.}) 8. Nb3 Be7 9. e3 dxe3 10. fxe3 {[%cal Be6e5,Be5e4]
In my opinion, this recapture is almost always a mistake. The problem is that
White's central structure is vulnerable to the advance ...e6-e5-e4. Of course,
White will soon play d3-d4 but his development is not sufficient to sustain
the integrity of the centre.} {In the game, Black started with} a5 {which is
always useful.} ({Even more to the point would have been} 10... e5 {[%cal
Ge5e4] when White should always reckon with the threat of ...e5-e4.} 11. d4 {
[%csl Bg2,Bc1,Bb3][%cal Be5e4,Bf7f5] The most principled reaction.} ({It goes
without saying that} 11. e4 $4 {[%csl Bd4] would be a terrible positional
mistake since this advance closes the g2-bishop and weakens the d4-square.
After} a5 {[%cal Ba5a4,Be7c5,Bf6g4] Black has a decisive advantage. He is
planning to proceed with ...a5-a4 followed by ...Bc5+ and eventually ...Ng4.})
11... Ng4 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] Remember this typical idea. Black is planning to
continue with ...e5-e4 followed by ...f7-f5, thus gaining space and closing
the g2-bishop.} ({The lazy approach} 11... exd4 12. exd4 a5 $15 {Leads to a
position which is easier for Black in view of White's vulnerable centre. The
threat of ...a5-a4 is really annoying.  A logical continuation would be} 13. d5
a4 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 a3 16. b3 Ng4 $15 {when Black has a very strong play
on the dark squares. The immediate threat is ...Bf6.}) 12. d5 {White cannot
avoid this commital advance.} ({Almost regardless of what our opponent does,
our next move is going to be ...e5-e4. For instance, the natural} 12. h3 {
is very well met by} e4 13. Ne1 {Unfortunately for White, there is no better
retreat square for the knight.} (13. Nfd2 Nxe3 $19) 13... Nh6 $17 {[%cal Bg2e4,
Bc8h3,Be7d6,Bd8g5,Bf7f5] Black has a huge advantage. The e4-pawn is indirectly
protected by the fact that h3 is hanging. At the same time, White's kingside
is very weak. By means of simple moves such as ...f7-f5 followed by ...Bd6,
and ...Qg5, Black is going to develop a devastating attack. Pay attention to
the fact that none of the white minor pieces is playing.}) {The following sequence
is pretty forced -} 12... e4 13. dxc6 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 exf3 15. Bxf3 Ne5 {It's
very important that this move comes with a tempo!} 16. Bg2 Nxc6 $15 {[%csl Bc4]
[%cal Bc6e5] Black is better due to his better structure and superior
development. The next move is going to be ...Ne5 when the attack on c4 is very
annoying.}) 11. d4 a4 12. Nbd2 {[%csl Be3,Bd4,Bc4][%cal Be6e5] A sad necessity.
With such a poor development, the white position is now quite vulnerable to ...
e6-e5.} Re8 {There is nothing wrong with this natural move. Now, ...e6-e5
would be even more effective.} ({The computer even suggests the strange-looking
} 12... Ra6 {The idea is that after} 13. Qe2 e5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ng4 16.
Nf3 Re6 $15 {Black will regain the e5-pawn, thus keeping his better pawn
structure. I provide this line just to show that after ...a7-a5, we can often
employ the rook via the 6th rank.}) 13. Kh1 a3 14. b3 Bb4 $6 {This move is a
bit pointless.} ({Black should have played the thematic} 14... e5 $1 15. Nxe5 (
{After} 15. d5 Nb4 $19 {[%cal Gc7c6] followed by ...c7-c6, Black is already
winning.}) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Ng4 17. Ne4 Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Nxe5 $19 {[%cal Gc8f5,
Gf5g4] Black's advantage is close to decisive. He will continue with either ...
Bg4 (f5) followed by ...Rad8. It's not clear how White is going to complete
the development.}) 15. Qc2 Ra5 16. c5 e5 17. Nc4 exd4 18. Nxa5 Bxa5 19. Nxd4
Nxd4 20. exd4 Qxd4 21. Bxa3 Ng4 22. Rad1 Qe5 23. Rd5 Qe7 24. Bc1 c6 25. Rd4 g6
26. Re4 Be6 27. Bb2 Qg5 28. h3 Nh6 29. Bc1 Qxg3 30. Bxh6 Bc7 31. Bf4 {1-0
White wins.} 1-0

