{From this example, we will start examining White's strategy based on the
early e2-e3 advance.  The first important starting position arises after} 1.
Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d4 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O Bc5 6. e3 {White wants to eliminate
Black's space advantage before the second player manages to complete the
development. Against this system, the most precise reaction is} Nge7 {[%csl
Be7,Bd4] Remember that we develop the knight on e7 only when White goes for
fast e2-e3. The point is that after the eventual exd4, the d4-square will be
weak. The e7-knight can join the fight for this square either via c6 or f5.} 7.
exd4 {The most principled move.} ({After} 7. e4 {[%cal Bd2d3] followed by
d2-d3, we get a position with a Closed centre which will be discussed a bit
later.}) {The following couple of moves are quite logical -} 7... Nxd4 8. Nxd4
Bxd4 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Ne2 {We can now see the point behind White's strategy.
After chasing the bishop away from the d4-square, White wants to follow with
d2-d4, claiming superiority in the centre. On the downside, the d4-pawn can
often be vulnerable. In the game, Black played the natural} Bf6 {which is
perfectly normal and playable.} ({In such positions, I would prefer leaving
the bishop on d4 since the weak d4-square and the backward d-pawn provide
Black will more than enough compensation for White's bishop pair. A very
logical continuation would have been} 10... Rb8 {[%csl Bd8,Be7,Bd1,Bc1][%cal
Bb7b6,Bc8b7] planning to proceed with ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7. A logical
line would be} 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. d3 b6 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 {[%csl Bd4,
Bd3][%cal Bc7c5,Bb7d7,Bf8d8,Be7f5,Bf5d4] After the favourable exchange of the
light-squared bishops, Black is already statically better. If left unbothered,
he will increase the pressure with simple moves such as ...c7-c5, and ...Nf5
followed by doubling the rooks along the d-file.} {Therefore, White can change
the pawn structure by playing} 15. Qe4 {Nevertheless, after} Qxe4 16. dxe4 Rd8
17. Be3 c5 18. Rfd1 Rbd7 $15 {[%csl Bd4,Be4,Bc4,Bf3][%cal Be7c6,Bf7f6,Bg8f7,
Bg7g5,Bh7h5,Bg5g4,Bc6e5,Bc6d4] Black has a slight but lasting advantage. Due
to the fixed pawn structure and the weak d4-square, the knight is definitely
superior to the bishop. After ...Nc6, Black can follow with either ...Ne5 or ..
.Nd4. Fixing the kingside structure ...g7-g5-g4 is another important idea in
this position.}) 11. d4 Nf5 {Putting maximum pressure on d4 and eventually
striking with ...e6-e5 is Black's main strategy in this position.} 12. Be3 {
Good or bad, White is forced to part with the bishop pair.} Nxe3 {Even though
there is nothing wrong with this move, it would be even more effective once
White has committed to d4-d5.} ({Better would have been the immediate} 12... e5
{The idea is that after provoking} 13. d5 {Black can play} Nxe3 14. fxe3 Be7 {
[%cal Be7c5,Bf7f5,Ba7a5,Ba8a6,Ba6g6,Bg6h6] With the white pawn on d5, our
bishop will be very effective on c5. Also, Black can consider improving the
position with ...f7-f5, followed by ...a7-a5, and ...Ra6-g6 (h6). Black has a
huge advantage.}) 13. fxe3 c6 {I find this move a bit passive and not in the
spirit of the position.} ({Once again, better would have been} 13... e5 $132)
14. Nc3 e5 15. d5 Bg5 16. Qe2 Qb6 17. Rae1 Bd7 18. Kh1 Rae8 19. e4 Be7 20. Rd1
Qc7 21. d6 Bxd6 22. Qd2 Re6 23. c5 Bxc5 24. Qxd7 Re7 25. Qxc7 Rxc7 26. Bh3 g6
27. Ne2 Kg7 28. Rd3 Re7 29. Rfd1 Rfe8 30. Rd7 Rxd7 31. Rxd7 Re7 32. Rxe7 Bxe7
33. Kg2 Kf6 34. Bc8 b6 35. Bd7 c5 36. Nc3 Kg7 37. Nd5 Bd8 38. Kf3 h5 39. Ke2
Kh6 40. a4 h4 41. g4 h3 42. Kf3 Bh4 43. Bc8 Kg5 44. Ne3 Be1 45. Bd7 Bd2 46. Nd1
Bf4 47. Nf2 Kh4 48. g5 Bxh2 49. Nxh3 Bg3 50. Kg2 Bf4 51. Be8 Bxg5 52. Bxf7 Kh5
53. Nxg5 Kxg5 54. Kf3 Kh5 55. b3 Kg5 56. Kg3 Kf6 57. Be8 Kg5 58. Bd7 Kh5 59.
Bc6 Kg5 60. Be8 Kh5 61. Kf3 Kg5 62. Ke3 Kh6 63. Kd3 g5 64. Bd7 Kh5 65. Ke3 Kh4
66. Kf3 a6 67. Bc8 b5 68. Bxa6 c4 69. Bxb5 cxb3 70. a5 b2 71. Bd3 Kh3 72. Kf2
Kh2 73. a6 g4 74. a7 g3+ 75. Kf3 b1=Q 76. Bxb1 g2 77. a8=Q g1=N+ 78. Kg4 Nh3
79. Qh8 Kg1 80. Kxh3 Kf2 81. Qxe5 Ke1 82. Qf4 Ke2 83. e5 Kd1 84. Bh7 Ke2 85. e6
Ke1 86. Qe3+ Kd1 87. Qf2 Kc1 88. Qc2# {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

