70,67,-44,-21,-28,-21,-28,-22,-42,0,-42,-25,-32,-6,-14,-20,-47,-56,-58,-19,-57,
-54,-10,0,0,0,-7,0,-47,-58,-62,-62,-51,-61,-103,-83,-86,-79,-70,-70,-70,-70,
-70,-70,-70,-70,-70,-70,-70,-70,-70]} {In this example, we will examine the
typical Benoni maneuver - Na3-c2.} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5.
O-O Bc5 6. d3 Nf6 7. Na3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ba3c2,Bb2b4] Remember this standard
move. White wants to prepare the advance b2-b4 by means of Nc2. Additionally,
in some lines, the c2-knight will be putting pressure on d4. On the other hand,
if Black manages to limit White's immediate counterplay, the c2-knight will
remain misplaced.} ({As we know, in this type of structure, White cannot play
passively. The following cooperative line is a good illustration of what might
happen if White plays without a plan -} 7. a3 a5 8. Re1 O-O 9. b3 e5 {[%csl
Bc5][%cal Bc5e7,Bf6d7,Bd7c5]} 10. Bb2 Be7 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5] After completing
the development and stabilizing the centre, we always go for this move.
Remember that the c5-square is reserved for the knight.} 11. Nbd2 Nd7 12. Rc1
Nc5 {[%csl Bc5,Bd2,Bc1,Bc2][%cal Bf8e8,Bf7f5,Be7f6,Be5e4] Black managed to
achieve his dream position. He is now ready to expand in the centre by playing
...f7-f5 and eventually ...e5-e4.}) 7... O-O 8. Nc2 e5 {[%csl Bd4,Be5][%cal
Bb2b4,Be8e1]} 9. b4 {White should opt for this move before Black plays .
..a7-a5. Otherwise, he will find himself in a position without any counterplay.
} Nxb4 10. Nxe5 {As we will see, the exchange of the b4-pawn for the one on e5
is favourable for Black. There are two reasons for such an evaluation: 1) The
d4-pawn keeps providing Black with a space advantage 2) Black can put annoying
pressure on the semi-open e-file} ({Another possibility would have been} 10.
Nxb4 Bxb4 11. Nxe5 {The nature of the position, however, remains unchanged.
The following line illustrates Black's best way of handling this structure.}
Re8 12. Nf3 Bc5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Be2e3,Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Ba8a6,Ba6e6,Bc8g4] An
important move which is designed to stabilize the d4-pawn and discourage any
e2-e3 ideas. If allowed, Black will increase the pressure with ...Bg4 followed
by ...a7-a5, and ...Ra6-e6. Sometimes, we can push the a-pawn all the way to
a4 in order to prevent the maneuver Nf3-d2-b3.} {Therefore, White should play}
13. Nd2 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Bd2b3] immediately. In this case, the logical
follow-up would be} a5 {[%cal Ga8a6,Gh7h5,Gh5h4]} 14. Nb3 Bf8 {[%cal Ba5a4]}
15. a4 {[%csl Bh2,Bg3,Bf2,Bg2]} h5 {[%cal Bh5h4] Remember this typical idea.
When the white knight is far away from the kingside, starting active actions
by employing the march of the h-pawn is very strong. The queenside rook can
also join the attack via the 6th rank.} 16. Bg5 {pinning the knight and
preventing ...h5-h4. Black's best idea in this position is the thematic} Bb4
$15 {[%csl Be1,Be2][%cal Ba8a6,Ba6e6,Bd8d6,Bf6h7,Bh5h4] closing the b-file and
taking the e1-square from the rook. In the future, the pressure on the e-file
will be combined with active actions on the kingside. After the maneuver ...
Ra6-e6, Black can get rid of the pin by playing ...Qd6 followed by ...Nh7.
Later on, the advance ...h5-h4 comes on the agenda again.}) 10... Re8 11. Nf3
Nxc2 12. Qxc2 c6 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Bc8f5,Bd8d7,Be8e2,Bh7h5,Bh5h4] Even though
Black's position remains slightly better, this move is not my cup of tea. The
problem is that our queen's rook cannot by activated via the 6th rank.} ({
I would have preferred} 12... a5 {[%cal Ga8a6] planning to follow with the
standard ...Ra6. An illustrative line would be} 13. Re1 Ra6 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6
Qxf6 {[%csl Be1][%cal Bc5b4,Ba6e6]} 16. Rab1 Bb4 17. Rf1 Rae6 {[%csl Be2,Bd4,
Bf3][%cal Be8e2,Bh6h5,Bh5h4] with an advantage for Black.}) 13. a4 Bf5 14. Ba3
Qd6 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Qb2 Rad8 17. Rfe1 Rd7 18. a5 Bg4 19. Qd2 Qh5 20. Qf4 c5
21. Rab1 Rde7 22. Rb5 h6 23. Qd6 b6 24. axb6 axb6 25. Rb2 Re6 26. Qc7 R8e7 27.
Qb8+ Re8 28. Qa7 Qf5 29. Rd2 Qh5 30. Qa4 Bxf3 31. Bxf3 Ng4 32. h4 g5 33. Kg2
