-109,-132,29,0,8] The next couple of examples are dedicated to the positions
with closed centre. As a rule, in this line, Black is more than ready to play
a position with a blocked centre. Nevertheless, one should know how to exactly
arrange the pieces.} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Bc5 6. d3
Nf6 7. e4 e5 {[%cal Bc7c5] The most principled choice. Before anything else,
we need to rule out the advance e4-e5. A very important factor is the position
of Black's c-pawn. Had this pawn been on c5, the structure would have been
perfectly balanced. With the pawn on c7-however, Black is better since the
c5-square can be used for the knight.} ({In this concrete position, the
alternative} 7... dxe3 8. Bxe3 Bxe3 9. fxe3 O-O {[%cal Be6e5,Be5e4] is
playable as well. As we already know, in this structure, the advance ...
e6-e5-e4 is pretty annoying for White.}) 8. Nh4 {Preparing the advance f2-f4
is White's only constructive idea in this pawn structure.} O-O 9. h3 {Of
course, before going for f2-f4, White should take the g4-square under control.
Otherwise, the resource ...Ng4 is quite annoying.} Re8 {With this useful move,
Black prepares the f8-square for the bishop. The vacant c5-square will be
occupied by the knight.} ({In my opinion, even more precise would have been} 
9... Nd7 {[%cal Bd8h4,Bd7c5,Bf2f4] Black not only prepares the knight transfer
to c5 but also prevents f2-f4 by targeting the h4-knight. The following lines
illustrate the nature of the arising positions.} 10. Na3 ({Black is very well
prepared for} 10. f4 {In this case, the automatic answer is} exf4 {You
shouldn't allow the advance f4-f5.} 11. Bxf4 (11. gxf4 $4 Qxh4 $19) 11... Nde5
{[%csl Bd4,Bd3][%cal Bc8e6,Bd8d7,Bf7f6,Ba7a5,Ba8b8,Bb7b5] The e5-knight
controls the entire board. After further stabilizing the position with moves
such as ...Be6, ...Qd7, and ...f7-f6, Black can start playing on the queenside
by preparing the advance ...b7-b5.}) 10... a5 {Gaining space on the queenside
is always useful.} 11. Nc2 Re8 {[%cal Bc5f8,Bd7c5] Black is ready to proceed
with the thematic ...Bf8 followed by ...Nc5.} {White's most principled way of
handling the position would be} 12. Nf5 Bf8 13. f4 {Nevertheless, after} Nc5 {
[%cal Bg7g6,Bf5h4,Be5f4,Bc8f5,Be5e4] White has no follow-up. Besides ...g7-g6,
Black is also threatening ...Bxf5 followed by ...e5-e4.} 14. fxe5 ({In case of
} 14. Kh2 Bxf5 15. exf5 e4 16. dxe4 Nxe4 $17 {The strong central passed as
well as the superior piece activity provide Black with a huge advantage.})
14... Nxe5 15. Ne1 a4 $17 {Black is controlling the entire board.}) 10. Na3 g6
11. Nc2 ({A typical response to} 11. f4 {is} Nh5 {[%csl Bh5] when White cannot
keep his kingside intact.}) 11... a5 {In my opinion, this move is less precise
since it allows Bg5 followed by f2-f4.} ({My choice would have been} 11... Nd7
{[%cal Gc5e7,Gd7c5]}) ({or} 11... Be7 {[%cal Gf6d7] with the idea of ...Nd7.
One of the ideas behind ...g7-g6 is that ...Be7 cannot be answered with Nf5.})
12. Bg5 Be7 {[%cal Bf6d7,Bd7c5]} 13. f4 $13 {The position is already unclear.
