{In this example, we will see why White cannot enter a proper Catalan with the
move 3.d4.} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. d4 {This is an attempt to get the Catalan.
There is, however, an important nuance - Black saved a tempo on ...Nf6. That's
the reason why we can solve all the problems in a concrete way.} dxc4 {[%cal
Gc7c5] This is the most precise reaction. Our next move is going to be ...
c7-c5.} 4. Bg2 {This is the most common continuation.} ({An important
alternative is} 4. Nf3 c5 5. Qa4+ {Without the inclusion of the moves Bg2 and .
..Nf6, Black has more than one way to equalize.} Nd7 $1 {In my opinion, this
is the most ambitious choice.} ({If you want to play rock-solid chess, my
suggestion would be} 5... Bd7 6. Qxc4 cxd4 {This is the safer choice.} ({
More ambitious is} 6... Bc6 {but after} 7. dxc5 Nd7 8. Be3 {Black still needs
to prove his compensation for the pawn. 0-1 (40) Sismanis, A (2191)-Rakhmanov, A
(2508) Athens op 2008 (3)}) 7. Bg2 Bc6 {Whenever, in Catalan type of positions,
Black manages to put his light-squared bishop on the long diagonal (without
making concessions), the problems are solved. A possible continuation would be}
8. O-O Nf6 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nbd7 {with an equal endgame. Of
course, we still have chances to outplay our opponent.}) 6. Bg2 a6 {[%cal
Gb7b5,Gc8b7] an important move. Black is planning to develop the queenside
with ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7.} 7. Qxc4 ({White can try to prevent ...b7-b5
with} 7. Nc3 {The problem with this concept is that sooner or later, White
will take the c4-pawn. Then, Black solves all his problems with ...b7-b5
followed by ...Bb7. The following illustrative line shows how Black should
handle this position.} Ngf6 8. O-O Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] removing the rook from
the opposition. White can no longer prevent the advance ...b7-b5. The most
logical follow-up is} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qxc4 b5 11. Qd3 Bb7 12. Bf4 Rc8 $15 {
Black is already slightly better. After castling, he will proceed with ...Qb6
followed by ...Rfd8. In this case, White will have to find a safe place for
his queen. Another important factor is that the d7-knight is superior to the
one on c3. This knight, often lands on c4, thus creating coordination problems
in White's camp.}) 7... b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8] with ...Rc8 to follow.
Black is already slightly better. 0-1 (58) Gholami,A (2489)-Pourramezanali,A 
(2525) Fajr op 26th Amol 2018 (6)}) 4... c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {[%cal Bg8f6,Be1g1]
Usually, this position arises with the moves 0-0 and ...Nf6 included. In such
a case, both Qa4 and dxc5 would create practical problems for Black. Now, 6.
dxc5 will be simply answered with ...Qxd1 when White will be forced to
recapture with the king.} 6. Qa4 {[%cal Bf3e5,Ba4c4] This is White's only try
to prove something. The immediate idea is Ne5.} cxd4 {Black can opt for this
continuation without any fear. Due to the fact that he saved a tempo on ...Nf6,
he has enough time to parry all White's threats.} 7. Nxd4 {Once again, the
only move.} ({After} 7. O-O Nge7 $1 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Be7f5,Bf8e7,Be8g8,Bc8d7,
Ba8c8] White is fighting for equality. Black will continue with ...Bd7
followed by ...Nf5, and ...Rc8. In this case, it will be very difficult for
White to restore the material balance.} 8. Rd1 ({White can try to regain the
missing material by means of} 8. Qxc4 Nf5 9. g4 Nd6 10. Qa4 {but the problem
is that the g4-pawn is now vulnerable. After} Bd7 11. Nxd4 Ne5 12. Qb3 Nxg4 $15
{Black enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 8... Bd7 9. Qxc4 Nf5 10. Bf4 Rc8 11. Na3
$2 {This move puts White on the verge of losing.} ({The lesser evil would have
been} 11. Qb3 {Even in this case, however, after} Be7 12. Qxb7 g5 13. Bd2 Rb8
14. Qa6 Rxb2 $17 {Black's advantage is undisputable.}) 11... e5 12. Bd2 {
This position was reached in the game 0-1 Rusev, K (2455)-Petkov, V (2480)
BUL-chT 56th Sunny Beach 2006 (2). Now, after} Bxa3 13. bxa3 O-O $19 {Black
would have obtained a winning advantage.}) ({White fails to restore the
material balance after} 7. Qxc4 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9. Bf4 {Trying to prevent ...
e6-e5 and preparing Rd1.} ({After} 9. Rd1 e5 10. e3 O-O 11. exd4 e4 $17 {
Black's superior development gives him an overwhelming initiative.}) 9... Ng4
$1 $17 {This is the key move. The advance ...e6-e5 cannot be prevented. Black
has a huge advantage.}) 7... Qxd4 8. Bxc6+ Bd7 9. Be3 $1 {White should play
this move in order to secure equality!} ({Another possible direction is} 9.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxc4 Rc8 11. Qf4 Bd6 12. Qd2 {This position was reached in the
game 0-1 Bindrich,F (2606)-Vokhidov,S (2480) Wch Blitz St Petersburg 2018 (10).
Now, the most energetic would have been} h5 {[%cal Bh5h4] with the threat of ..
.h5-h4. After} 13. h4 Nf6 14. Nc3 Be5 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {[%cal Bh8a1]} 16. Bd2
Rhd8 $15 {the arising endgame is slightly better for Black in view of his
superior development and the pressure on the diagonal h8-a1. White still needs
to work hard in order to reach equality.}) {The following couple of moves are
quite forced -} 9... Bxc6 10. Qxc6+ Qd7 11. Qxc4 Rc8 12. Qb3 Bc5 13. O-O Bxe3
14. Qxe3 a6 15. Nc3 Nf6 $11 {Of course, the position is equal. That being said,
in a practical game, we will keep playing. The following cooperative line
shows how things can go wrong for White -} 16. Rfd1 Qe7 {[%cal Bc8c1]} 17. Kg2
O-O 18. Qf3 Rc4 19. Rac1 Rfc8 {[%cal Bb7b5,Bb5b4,Bf6d5,Bc8c1] Usually, in this
type of symmetrical position, c-file is much more important than the d-file.
The reason is that the black king is closer to the d-file that the white king
to the c-file. A typical idea would be ...b7-b5-b4 followed by ...Nd5 which
closes the d-file.} *

