[PlyCount "18"]

{[%evp 0,18,14,7,23,0,19,9,14,10,14,23,15,10,11,10,19,9,4,13,39] Very often we
should be ready to play Hedgehog type of positions. In the examples below, I
will try to provide a brief coverage of the most important ideas you should
know this fundamental pawn structure. We will usually get the Hedgehog via the
following move order -} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 e6 5. Nc3 Be7 6.
O-O O-O 7. b3 c5 8. d4 {If White is ready to play the Hedgehog, sooner or
later, he should go for this move.} ({The alternative approach} 8. Bb2 d6 9. e3
Nbd7 10. Qe2 {is extensively covered in separate model games.}) 8... cxd4 9.
Qxd4 {This is the most ambitious continuation. White is ready to put pressure
on d6 by means of Rd1 and even Ba3.} ({Of course, White can also recapture
with the knight} 9. Nxd4 {when after} Bxg2 10. Kxg2 a6 {we get again our
Hedgehog.}) 9... d6 {We have reached the Hedgehog structure. Despite White's
space advantage, Black's position is extremely solid and flexible. As we will
see in the coming examples, Black has plenty of resources to protect the
d6-pawn. As always, we have two main ideas in the Hedgehog - ...b6-b5, and ...
d6-d5. I must say that the advance ...b6-b5 is more characteristic for the
English Hedgehog. The reason is that being far away from the diagonal
f1-a6, White's light-squared bishop cannot control the b5-square. In this
version of the Hedgehog, the advance ...d6-d5 usually leads to simplifications
and equality. Most of the endgames are quite comfortable for Black. In order
to give you a better idea of how to handle them, I include examples from
one of my camp lectures featuring the Hedehog endgames. In the following,
examples, you shall see some of the most important typical ideas in the
English Hedgehog.} *

