{[%evp 0,80,14,7,34,4,19,7,9,10,14,5,15,-3,-5,13,13,14,24,30,45,43,48,61,67,57,
68,75,73,50,53,49,52,53,53,46,45,45,55,46,42,33,33,27,60,39,33,65,55,49,69,35,
72,11,89,42,64,31,28,28,3,28,32,26,31,42,44,46,38,-18,-3,-2,-2,-15,-16,-16,-7,
-7,-7,-7,0,-8,-8] Let's take a look at the position arising after} 1. Nf3 Nf6
2. c4 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Be7 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 c5 8. Nc3 d6 9. d4
cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 {Usually, the positions arising after the exchange
of the light-squared bishops are harmless for Black. Our idea is to execute
the advance ...b6-b5. Very often, in order to reduce White's control of the
b5-square, we exchange a pair of knights by means of ...Nc6. White's most
dangerous plan in this structure is e2-e4, f2-f4 followed by Qf3. Later on,
White starts seizing kingside space with g3-g4-g5. A very good move in this
position is} Qc8 {planning to transfer the queen to the perfect b7-square.} ({
Another typical idea is} 11... a6 12. e3 Ra7 {In Hedgehog structures, the rook
is usually well placed on the 7th rank. Very often Black prepares ...b6-b5
with ...Rb7. Another typical idea is to prepare the move ...Nc6 by playing ...
Qc8 followed by ...Rc7.} 13. Qf3 {White is fighting for the c6-square.} ({
Another principled direction is} 13. f4 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gg3g4,Gg4g5] Planning Qf3
followed by g3-g4-g5. In this case, Black equalizes by} d5 ({If you are
looking for a more complicated position, a decent alternative would be} 13...
Qc8 14. Qf3 Rc7 15. Rac1 Nc6 $132 {with enough counterplay.}) 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15.
Nxd5 Qxd5+ 16. Qf3 Qxf3+ 17. Kxf3 Rc7 18. Rac1 Rfc8 19. Rxc7 Rxc7 $11 {The
arising endgame is equal.}) 13... Qc8 {planning Rc7 with Nbd7 or Nc6 to follow}
14. Na4 (14. Rfd1 Rc7 15. Rac1 Nbd7 $132) 14... Rb7 15. Rac1 Qd7 16. Nc3 Rc8
17. Rfd1 Rbc7 18. e4 Nc6 19. Na4 Rb7 20. Nxc6 Qxc6 21. e5 dxe5 22. Qxc6 Rxc6
23. Bxe5 Nd7 24. Bb2 b5 25. cxb5 Rxc1 26. Rxc1 axb5 27. Rc8+ Bf8 28. Nc3 b4 29.
Na4 f5 {1/2 Karpov,A (2730)-Wahls,M (2525)/Biel 1990/(61)}) 12. e4 Qb7 13. f3
a6 14. Qe2 {For the time being, White is trying to restrict Black's
counterplay based on ...b6-b5.} Rc8 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black wants to take with the
rook after the exchange of knights on c6. By exchanging the d4-knight, we make
the advance ...b6-b5 easier.} ({The alternative} 14... Nbd7 15. Rad1 Rfe8 {
is possible as well. White's problem is that he does not have a constructive
plan. When he tries to play for a win usually this increases Black`s dynamical
possibilities as shows the following example:} 16. h4 (16. Rfe1 Bf8 17. Qf2
Rad8 18. Re2 g6 {1/2 Nei,I (2495)-Tal,M (2555)/Tallinn 1981/(26)}) 16... Qc7
17. Qd2 Rad8 18. Rc1 Ne5 19. g4 Qb7 20. g5 Nfd7 21. f4 $6 {In Hedgehog
positions, we are usually happy to provoke our opponent to overextend his
position.} ({Better would have been} 21. Rcd1) 21... Nc5 $1 {[%cal Gd8d2]
White has probably missed this powerful blow.} 22. Rce1 Ned3 23. Re3 Nxb2 24.
Qxb2 Bf8 25. Qe2 g6 26. b4 Bg7 $1 27. Rd1 $2 {1/2 MacKay, I-Hansen, L (2455)/
Adelaide 1988/(72)} (27. Nf3 Bxc3 28. bxc5 Bg7 29. cxb6 Qxb6) {In this
position, Black could have played} 27... Bxd4 $1 28. Rxd4 e5 $1 29. fxe5 $140
Ne6 $19) 15. Rfd1 Nc6 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 17. Rd2 Rac8 18. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1e3] This
manoeuvre allows White to prepare for the advance b6-b5 and keep the control
over c4-square.} ({Trying to prevent ...b6-b5 with} 18. a4 {is usually not a
good idea. Our typical reaction should be} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5] Whenever you
see the move a2-a4, you need to transfer the knight to c5. In this case, the
b3-pawn is going to be quite vulnerable.} 19. Re1 Nc5 20. Qd1 {Black is
already doing fine. Besides the different waiting moves that we can make, a
very good idea would be} Bg5 $5 {Once again, we provoke our opponent to
overextend his position. After} 21. f4 Bf6 $132 {Black has an excellent
counterplay in view of the vulnerable pawns on b3 and e4.}) 18... b5 19. Ne3
Ne8 {[%cal Ge7g5] A standard way to protect d6 in hedgehog positions. In the
following game, Black had no problems to maintain the balance:} 20. Rad1 Bg5 $5
{You should already get used to this typical provocative move!} 21. f4 (21. h4
Bxe3 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Qxe3 b4) 21... Bd8 $5 (21... Bf6 22. Bxf6 Nxf6 23. Qf3
Ne8 24. e5 Qe7) 22. Qf3 Ba5 23. Rf2 Bb6 24. Bd4 h6 25. Bxb6 Rxb6 (25... Qxb6)
26. Rfd2 Rbc6 27. e5 Qb8 $1 {forcing White to take on d6} (27... dxe5 $6 28.
Rd7 Qb8 29. Ng4 $1 exf4 $140 $2 (29... R6c7 30. Nxe5 (30. fxe5 Qa8 $14) 30...
Nf6 31. R7d2 bxc4 32. bxc4 $14) 30. Nxh6+ $1 gxh6 (30... Kh7 31. Nxf7 $18) 31.
Qh5 Nd6 32. R1xd6 $18) 28. exd6 Rxd6 (28... Nxd6 $2 29. c5 Ne8 30. b4 $16) 29.
f5 Rxd2+ (29... bxc4 30. Nxc4 Rxd2+ 31. Rxd2 exf5 32. Qxf5 Rd8) 30. Rxd2 Nf6 $1
{here the isolation of e-pawn is not dangerous for Black because of reduced
material} 31. fxe6 fxe6 32. Ng4 Nxg4 33. Qxg4 Qb7+ 34. Kg1 Qc6 (34... Qb6+ 35.
Qd4 Qxd4+ 36. Rxd4 Kf7) 35. Re2 (35. cxb5 axb5 36. Re2 Qc5+ 37. Kg2 Qd5+ 38.
Kh3 Rc6) 35... bxc4 36. Qxe6+ Qxe6 37. Rxe6 c3 38. Re1 Rd8 39. Rc1 Rd2 40. Rxc3
Rxa2 {and after 8 moves the draw was agreed, 1/2 Polugaevsky, L (2625)
-Gheorghiu,F (2540)/Riga 1979/IZT (48)} *

