{The next example, features a very important move order based on the Ba3 idea.
} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. b3 c5 8. d4
cxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Rd1 {This is White's most flexible move order. For the
time being, he does not clarify the position of his dark-squared bishop. For
instance, in case of 10...a6, White will play immediately 11.Ba3 when ...Nc5
is impossible.} Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gd7c5] Since Ba3 is already a threat, we
should start with this move. Now, Ba3 can be met with ...Nc5.} 11. e4 $5 {
This tricky move creates an interesting positional trap. Black should be very
careful at this point.} ({It goes without saying that} 11. Nb5 $6 Ne8 {does
not create any problems for Black. Very soon, the white knight will get kicked
back.}) 11... Qc8 $1 {This is the most elegant way of neutralizing White's
pressure.} ({White's point is that the natural} 11... a6 $6 {will be met by}
12. Ba3 Nc5 13. e5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Nxe5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $14 {with a slight
but lasting edge for White. The weakness of the c6-square as well as the
vulnerable b6-pawn is a constant source of worry in this endgame. Black should
always reckon with moves like Nc6 and Na4. At the same time, White can gain
kingside space with f2-f4 followed by Kf3 and g3-g4-g5. In the endgame section
of this lecture, you will find more details about this position.}) 12. Bb2 {
White has nothing better than this natural move.} ({Now,} 12. Ba3 {is
pointless since after} Nc5 {the move e4-e5 wouldn't lead to an exchange of the
queens. This is the point behind 11...Qc8.}) 12... a6 13. Nd2 Qc7 {Black
managed to achieve a comfortable version of the Hedgehog. White's main problem
is the lack of constructive plans. Additionally, finding a suitable place for
the queen is not easy. Black always tries to oppose his rooks to the white
queen.} 14. Rac1 Rad8 15. b4 Rc8 {After b3-b4, the c4-pawn is weakened and
putting the rook on c8 makes a lot of sense.} 16. a3 Rfe8 17. h3 Bf8 {This is
a typical regrouping in Hedgehog type of positions. The bishop shouldn't be on
the way of the rook. For instance, when the white queen is on e3, Black can
often carry out the advance ...d6-d5.} 18. Re1 h5 {This is another typical
idea to remember. The advance ...h7-h5 is especially effective when White has
committed to h2-h3. Black's idea is to further weaken the kingside by means of
...h5-h4. The following shuffling around with the pieces is quite typical for
the Hedgehog.} 19. Bf1 Rcd8 20. Qe3 Qb8 21. Nf3 Ba8 22. Rcd1 Rc8 23. Be2 Qb7
24. Bf1 d5 $5 {[%cal Ge8e3] We should make very precise calculations before
going for this central break. It turns out that it works perfectly fine now.}
25. Nd2 $6 {This is already an inaccuracy.} ({The principled continuation was} 
25. cxd5 exd5 26. Ng5 a5 $132 {Even though the position remains balanced,
Black's play is practically easier in view of White's exposed queen and
vulnerable king.}) ({Before pushing ...d6-d5, we should always calculate} 25.
e5 $2 {This time, Black is winning by means of} d4 $1 26. Rxd4 Nxe5 $19) 25...
a5 $1 {Another typical move. By deflecting the b4-pawn, Black makes the
c5-square available for the bishop. White's position is already very shaky.}
26. bxa5 $2 {A mistake in a difficult position.} ({The lesser evil would have
been} 26. cxd5 exd5 $15) 26... bxa5 $17 {[%cal Gf8c5] Black has a huge
advantage. The threat of ...Bc5 is very annoying. Later on, Grischuk managed
to convert his advantage.} 27. Rb1 dxe4 28. Ncxe4 Nxe4 29. Qxe4 Qxe4 30. Nxe4
Bxe4 31. Rxe4 Rb8 32. Ree1 Rb3 33. Red1 Reb8 34. Rxd7 Rxb2 35. Rxb2 Rxb2 36.
Rd8 g6 37. Ra8 a4 38. c5 Rc2 39. c6 Rxc6 40. Rxa4 Rc3 41. Ra8 Kg7 42. a4 Bc5
43. g4 hxg4 44. hxg4 Rg3+ 45. Bg2 Rxg4 46. Kf1 Rb4 47. Bc6 Rb1+ 48. Ke2 Rb2+
49. Kd3 Bxf2 50. a5 Ra2 51. a6 g5 52. Bb5 g4 53. Rc8 g3 54. Rc4 f5 {0-1 (54)
Agdestein,S (2602)-Grischuk,A (2737) Doha 2016} *

