{[%evp 0,86,32,30,27,-7,9,11,20,15,19,17,17,17,30,30,20,18,37,2,7,-6,17,3,-4,
-4,45,45,51,46,38,34,64,15,59,25,25,-4,-16,-26,37,-6,-6,-6,-6,-6,-11,-11,-11,
-31,-31,-31,-31,-102,-102,-88,-88,-88,-99,-178,-192,-188,-188,-200,-183,-227,
-180,-284,-301,-307,-294,-299,-294,-306,-311,-311,-305,-315,-312,-339,-209,
-212,-212,-226,-207,-226,-219,-29981,-29982] In this example, we shall see how
problematic the white queen can be in Hedgehog positions.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5
({Of course, our move order starts with} 2... b6) 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7
6. O-O Be7 {Here we will study some typical ideas for Black in so-called
hedgehog positions which arise after pawn exchange on d4.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. e4 O-O 10. Qe3 a6 11. Nd4 Qc7 12. b3 Nbd7 13. Bb2 ({Another typical
example is} 13. Ba3 {e.g.} Rfe8 14. h3 Bf8 15. Rfe1 Rad8 16. Rad1 Nc5 17. f3 g6
18. g4 Bg7 19. Bb2 Ba8 20. Re2 h6 21. Rde1 Qb8 22. Qd2 {[%cal Gd8d2]} e5 $1 {
After making all the preparatory moves, Black finds an elegant way of
exploiting the opposition along the d-file.} 23. Nc2 b5 24. cxb5 $2 {
overlooking Black`s intermediate move} (24. Ne3 bxc4 25. bxc4 Ne6 $15) 24... d5
$1 {[%csl Rb2,Rd2,Re1][%cal Gd8d2,Gc5d3]} 25. exd5 Nxd5 26. Nxd5 Rxd5 27. Qe3
Nd3 28. Rb1 Nxb2 29. Rxb2 e4 30. Rb1 Rd3 31. Qf2 exf3 32. Rxe8+ Qxe8 33. Bf1
Rc3 34. Rd1 (34. bxa6 $2 Rxc2 $1 35. Qxc2 Bd4+ 36. Kh1 f2+ 37. Bg2 Qe1+) 34...
axb5 $19 35. Nd4 Qe4 $1 36. Bxb5 (36. Nxb5 {decides} Rc2 37. Rd2 Rxd2 38. Qxd2
Bf6 $1 {[%cal Gf3f2,Gf6g5,Gg5h4,Gg5e3]} 39. Qf2 Bc6 40. Kh1 Bh4 $1 41. Qxh4 f2+
42. Kh2 Qh1+ 43. Kg3 Qf3+ 44. Kh2 g5) 36... Rc1 $1 {0-1 Uhlmann,W (2555)
-Boensch,U (2365)/Halle 1976}) 13... Rfe8 14. h3 ({Here is another example in
which the advance ...d6-d5 worked perfectly fine.} 14. Rfd1 Rad8 15. Rac1 Qb8
16. h3 Bf8 17. Re1 Nc5 18. Rcd1 g6 19. Qc1 Bg7 20. Qc2 Rc8 21. Qe2 (21. Qb1 Qa8
{[%csl Re4][%cal Ge6e5]}) 21... d5 $1 {[%cal Ge8e2]} 22. e5 Nfe4 23. Nf3 (23.
Nxe4 dxe4 24. f4 Nd3 25. Rf1 Nxb2 26. Qxb2 f6 27. exf6 Bxf6 $132) 23... Nxc3
24. Bxc3 dxc4 25. bxc4 Qc7 26. Bd4 Red8 $132 {0-1 Peng,Z (2460)-Van der Wiel,J
(2501)/Wijk aan Zee 2002/(60)}) (14. Rfe1 Bf8 15. Rad1 g6 16. Qd2 Rac8 17. Re2
Qb8 18. Qe1 Red8 19. f3 h5 $5 20. Kh1 Ba8 21. h3 Bg7 22. Red2 Bh6 23. Re2 Bg7
24. Red2 Bh6 {1/2 Novikov,I (2614)-Brodsky,M (2512)/Koszalin 1999}) 14... Bf8
15. Rae1 (15. Rfe1 Rad8 16. Re2 g6 17. Rae1 Qb8 18. Qd2 Bg7 {Black makes his
standard moves when is not easy for White to find a good plan} 19. Qd1 Nc5 20.
Bc1 Rc8 {intending to relocate the rooks on c- and d-files} 21. Bg5 h6 22. Bc1
Red8 23. Bb2 b5 $5 {the beginning of interesting complications which require
accuracy from White} 24. cxb5 d5 $1 25. exd5 ({We always need to consider} 
25. e5 Nfe4 26. a4 (26. Nc6 Bxc6 27. bxc6 Nxc3 28. Bxc3 Rxc6 $132) 26... Bxe5 (
26... Qxe5 $2 27. Nxe4 dxe4 28. b4 $1 Nd3 29. Nc6 Nxb2 30. Qxd8+ Rxd8 31. Nxe5
Bxe5 32. Bxe4 $16) 27. bxa6 (27. b4 Nxc3 28. Bxc3 Ne4 29. Nc6 Nxc3 30. Nxb8
Nxd1 31. Nxa6 Nc3 32. Rxe5 Nxa4) 27... Bxa6 28. Ncb5 {with an unclear play})
25... Nxd5 26. Nxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd8d1]} 27. b4 $1 {the best reply} Bxg2
28. Kxg2 e5 $1 29. bxc5 exd4 30. Rd2 $6 (30. bxa6 $2 d3) (30. Qd3 axb5 31. Rc1
Qa8+ $140 32. Kh2 Qxa2 33. Ba3 Qd5 34. Rb2) (30. Qb3 $5 Qxb5 (30... Rxc5 31.
bxa6 $1 Rb5 32. Qf3 Rxb2 $140 $2 33. a7) 31. Qxb5 axb5 32. Rc1 {with probable
draw}) 30... Rxc5 31. bxa6 Qa8+ 32. Qf3 Qxa6 $15 33. Red1 Rf5 34. Qe4 Qa4 (
34... Rfd5) 35. a3 Re8 36. Qb7 Rd8 37. Rd3 $6 (37. Qe4) 37... h5 38. R1d2 Qe8
$1 {[%cal Gd8b8,Ge8e1,Ge8e4]} 39. Kf1 $2 Rb8 40. Qc7 Rxb2 $1 41. Rxb2 Qe4 42.
