{The advance h7-h5-h4 in hedgehog positions. In some cases, the advance of
the rook`s pawn can be effective for creating counterplay as shown two following
games of Ftacnik.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7
7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 a6 (8... d6 {when} 9. e3 Nbd7 10. d4 {can be met by} Ne4 $132)
9. d4 (9. e3 d6 10. d4 cxd4 11. exd4 Nbd7 12. d5 e5) 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 d6 11.
e4 Nbd7 12. Rfd1 Qc7 13. Rac1 (13. Qe3 {for example:} Rfe8 14. Rac1 (14. Nd4
Bf8 15. Rac1 Rad8 16. h3 Qb8 17. Re1 g6 18. Rcd1 Ba8 19. Qd2 Bg7 20. Qc2 Rc8
21. Qb1 Bb7 22. Re2 Rcd8 23. Red2 Ba8 24. Re2 Nc5 25. Rde1 Nfd7 $13 {1/2
Polugaevsky,L-Williams,A/Buenos Aires ol/1978/(54)}) 14... Bf8 15. Nd4 Rad8 16.
Re1 Qb8 17. Qe2 g6 18. Rcd1 Bg7 19. Qc2 Nc5 20. Kh1 Qa8 21. f3 Qb8 22. Qf2 Ba8
23. Ba1 $13 {1/2 Karpov,An-Ribli,Z/Linares/1981/(23)}) 13... Rad8 (13... Rac8
14. Qe3 Rfe8 15. Nd4 Qb8 16. Re1 Bf8 17. Qd2 Qa8 18. f3 Qb8 19. Qe2 g6 20. Rcd1
Bg7 21. Nc2 Red8 22. Ne3 Bc6 23. Bf1 h5 24. Ba1 Ne5 $13 {[%emt 0:00:01]
Arbakov,V-Brodskij,M/Smolensk/1991/(60)}) 14. h3 (14. Qe3) 14... Rfe8 15. Kh2
$6 {[%cal Gc7h2] Here white king stays in opposition with black queen.} (15.
Qe3 Bf8 16. Nd4) (15. Nd2 Qb8 16. Qd3 Bc6 17. b4 Ba8 18. a3 Rc8 19. f4 {
1/2 Panno,O (2465)-Loiterstein,M (2260)/Buenos Aires 1998/(30)}) 15... Nc5 $1
16. Ne1 (16. Re1 $6 e5 17. Qe3 Ncxe4 18. Nd5 Bxd5 (18... Qc5 19. Nd4 $1 exd4
20. Bxd4 Qc8 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 23. Qxe7 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Qc6+ 25. f3
Re8 26. Qa7 Ra8 27. Qe7 Re8) 19. cxd5 Qb7 20. Nd2 Nxd2 21. Qxd2 Nd7 $15) (16.
Nd2) 16... h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 17. Qe3 $6 {Allows Black to weaken White`s
kingside pawn structure.} (17. f4 h4 18. gxh4 (18. g4 e5 (18... d5 19. e5 (19.
exd5 $2 Bd6) 19... dxc4 20. Qxc4 b5 21. Qe2 Rxd1 22. Nxd1 Nd5 23. Bxd5 Bxd5 24.
Bd4 (24. b4 Bc4 25. Rxc4 bxc4 26. bxc5 Bxc5) 24... Ba8 {[%cal Gc7b7]} 25. Nf2
b4 26. Qc4 Rc8 27. Qxb4 Bb7 $44) 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Qe3 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Ne6 $132)
18... Nh5 $5 (18... e5 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Qe3 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Ne6 22. Nd5 Nxd5 23.
cxd5 Nf4 $132) 19. b4 Nd7 20. Nd3 Bxh4 $132) (17. Kg1 h4 18. g4 Qb8 19. b4 e5
20. Qe3 Ne6 21. Qxb6 Nd4 22. Nc2 Rc8 23. Nxd4 Bd8 24. Nc6 Rxc6 25. Qe3 Rxc4 26.
a3) 17... h4 $1 18. Kh1 (18. gxh4 {then} Ncxe4 $1 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 $140
Bxe4 21. Qxe4 d5+ 22. Be5 Bd6 23. cxd5 Bxe5+ 24. Kg2 exd5 25. Rxc7 dxe4 26. Re7
Kf8 27. Rxd8 Kxe7 28. Rxe8+ Kxe8 {with a favourable ending for Black.}) 18...
hxg3 19. fxg3 $6 (19. Qxg3) 19... Nh7 20. Nf3 Bf6 21. Rc2 Qb8 22. g4 $2 {
This move only creates new weaknesses in White`s position.} (22. Re1) 22... Qa8
$1 (22... Bxc3 23. Qxc3 e5 24. Nd2 Ng5 25. Qe3 Nge6 {followed by Nf4, but the
text is more unpleasant for White.}) 23. Nd4 d5 $1 24. e5 (24. cxd5 exd5 25. e5
) 24... Bg5 25. Qe2 dxc4 26. Qxc4 Bxg2+ (26... Be3 $5) 27. Rxg2 Nf8 $1 {
[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g6,Ga8h1] This manoeuvre is decisive.} 28. b4 (28. Qf1 Ng6
29. Nf3 Bf4 $19) 28... Ncd7 (28... Ng6 $1 29. bxc5 bxc5 30. Nc2 (30. Qxc5 Rc8
31. Qa5 Nh4 32. Rdg1 Be3 $19) 30... Rxd1+ 31. Nxd1 Nh4 32. Qf1 Rd8 33. Nce3 Rd2
34. Bc3 Rxa2 $19) 29. Qc6 $1 {The most tenacious.} (29. Re1 $2 Ng6 $19) 29...
Nxe5 30. Qxa8 (30. Qxb6 Nc4 31. Qc6 Rxd4 $1 $19) 30... Rxa8 31. Ne4 Be7 32.
Nxe6 Nxe6 33. Bxe5 Bxb4 34. Bd6 (34. Rb2 a5 35. Bg3 $17) 34... Rad8 35. Rb2 $2
{The final mistake in time trouble.} (35. Rgg1 Bxd6 36. Nxd6 Re7 37. Ne4 $17)
35... Nc5 $1 36. Nxc5 (36. Rxb4 Nxe4 $19) (36. Nf6+ gxf6 37. Rxb4 Ne4 $19) (36.
Ng3 Ne4 $19) 36... bxc5 37. Rb3 (37. Rbb1 Re3 38. Kg2 Re2+ 39. Kf3 Rxa2 $19)
37... Re6 38. a3 (38. Rbd3 c4 $19) 38... Rexd6 39. Rxd6 Rxd6 40. axb4 Rb6 {
0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

