{The next instructive fragment is taken from the practice of my trainer GM
Viktor Gavrikov. We see a typical Hedgehog endgame type of position. Despite
having a space advantage, White lacks constructive ideas. Since three pairs of
minor pieces have been already exchanged, White's position is already quite
overextended. In this position, Gavrikov carried out the thematic} 26... b5 $1
27. cxb5 axb5 {[%csl Be7,Bf4,Bd6,Bb5,Ba2,Bc3,Be4] Once again, we have reached
this typical pawn structure. Black is already better since White has many
vulnerable points. The backward pawn on a2 as well as the weak c3-square might
become very important in the future. At some point, the e4-pawn might also
become vulnerable. Additionally, there are no stable squares for the white
knight.} 28. h5 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gd1h1,Gh5g6] After opening up the h-file, White
wants to proceed with Kg2 followed by Rh1. In reality, however, he does not
have enough resources for a kingside attack.} Qg5 29. Kg2 Rc7 30. hxg6 hxg6 31.
Nh3 Qc5 32. Qf4 Kg7 33. Re2 Rh8 {[%cal Gc5h5,Gh8h3] Suddenly, it becomes clear
that Black is the one who is attacking on the kingside. The threat now is ...
Qh5. Therefore, White decided to play} 34. e5 {which is a major concession.}
Qc6+ {With this move, Gavrikov forces the transition into an endgame that is
quite favourable for Black.} 35. Qe4 Qxe4+ 36. Rxe4 d5 {Contrary to the
previous example, White has now a pawn on e5 (instead of e3). This is an even
more favourable version for Black because the d5-pawn is a strong passed pawn.}
37. Re2 Rhc8 38. Nf4 Ba3 {An interesting way of fixing the a2-pawn. Now, Black
has all the time in the world to improve his position.} 39. Nd3 Kf8 40. Kf3 Rc3
{The vulnerable c3-square finally comes in handy!} 41. Ke3 Bc5+ {Gavrikov
decides to reroute his bishop to the diagonal a7-g1. Obviously, the bishop is
very strong in this position.} 42. Kd2 Bb6 43. Ke1 Ba5 44. Kf1 Ke7 45. Rb2 R8c7
46. Rbb1 {This move is probably not so precise because it allows ...Rc2.
Nevertheless, it's not easy to provide White with good advise here.} Rc2 47. a4
bxa4 48. bxa4 Ra2 49. Ra1 Rcc2 50. Rxa2 Rxa2 $17 {White is going to lose his
a4-pawn. Since the pawns are on one wing, White can still put up a lot of
resistance. After a long fight, Gavrikov managed to convert his advantage.} 51.
Rb1 Rxa4 52. Rb7+ Kf8 53. Nc5 Ra1+ 54. Kg2 Be1 55. f4 Ra2+ 56. Kh3 Ra3 57. Rb3
Ra7 58. Kg2 Rc7 59. Nd3 Bc3 60. Kf3 Ke7 61. g4 Kd7 62. f5 gxf5 63. gxf5 Bd4 64.
fxe6+ Kxe6 65. Kf4 Rc4 66. Rb7 Bxe5+ 67. Kf3 Bd6 68. Nf2 Rc3+ 69. Ke2 f5 70.
Rh7 Bf4 71. Rh8 d4 72. Nd3 Be3 73. Re8+ Kf7 74. Rb8 Rc2+ 75. Kf3 Rd2 76. Rb3
Ke6 77. Ra3 Kd5 78. Ra5+ Kc4 79. Ne5+ Kc3 80. Rc5+ Kb4 81. Rc8 Rf2+ 82. Kg3 f4+
83. Kg4 Rf1 84. Rc7 Kb3 85. Rc8 Rd1 86. Rd8 Kc3 87. Rc8+ Kd2 {0-1 Black wins.}
0-1

