{[%evp 0,80,36,30,26,34,27,30,10,-9,-5,10,37,38,25,16,51,-9,-2,2,70,30,55,70,
85,55,47,21,15,18,10,14,14,9,45,26,59,33,34,29,49,41,42,36,33,13,16,22,22,-30,
31,48,99,12,31,49,49,11,20,34,40,-1,0,-16,-53,-72,2,-33,-24,-71,-70,-92,-105,
-154,-183,-164,-200,-240,-94,-358,-350,-362,-425] In this model game, we shall
see how effective can be the advance of the kingside pawns in Hedgehog type of
endgames. This strategy is very well combined with the break ...b6-b5.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 b6 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O d6 8. c4 Be7 9.
Nc3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 a6 11. Bf3 Qc7 12. Bxb7 Qxb7 13. Qf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 $6 {
This is a dubious decision. In Hedgehog, Black very much likes to play against
a compromised pawn structure.} Nbd7 15. b3 Rc8 {[%cal Gb6b5] Besides bringing
the rook to a more active position, this move introduces the threat of ...
b6-b5. The advance ...b6-b5 is always on the agenda when the c3-knight is
weakened by the move b2-b3.} 16. Rac1 Bd8 {[%csl Be7][%cal Bd8c7,Bc7b8,Bg7g5,
Be8e7] I like this idea very much! Black is freeing the e7-square for the king.
On the other hand, the bishop will be redirected to b8. Later on, Black can
start expanding on the kingside. At the same time. White does not have any
constructive ideas.} 17. Rfd1 Bc7 18. Bg3 Bb8 19. Ne4 {What else? By provoking
...Nxe4, White wants to increase his central control. The lack of structural
flexibility, however, will keep posing problems. At the same time, Black's
plan is pretty straightforward.} Nxe4 20. fxe4 Ke7 {[%csl Bg3][%cal Bg7g5,
Bh6h5,Bh5h4] It's already clear that Black wants to proceed with ...g7-g5
followed by ...h6-h5. In order to save the bishop, White should accept further
concessions.} 21. f3 g5 22. Kf2 Rhg8 23. h3 h5 24. Rd2 Nf6 {White's position
is getting harder and harder. Due to the vulnerable e4-pawn, White should
always reckon with the idea of ...g5-g4.} 25. Rcd1 Rgd8 26. Ne2 {Trying to
increase the pressure on d6. However, this pawn is sufficiently protected. Now,
Kovalenko executes the thematic} b5 $1 {Very often, the kingside play is well
combined with this typical break.} 27. cxb5 axb5 28. a3 e5 $19 {[%csl Be2,Bg3]
I like this move a lot. Now, both white minor pieces are out of play. Black is
strategically winning. The final moves are also very instructive.} 29. Bh2 {
[%cal Be2g3,Bg3f5]} h4 30. Rg1 Rg8 31. Rg2 Ke6 32. Ke1 Nd7 33. b4 Nb6 34. f4 f6
35. fxg5 fxg5 36. Rf2 g4 37. hxg4 Rxg4 38. Rf5 Rh8 39. Ng1 Rxe4 40. Rg5 Rxe3+ {
0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

