{Now, we shall take a look at one of my blitz games. In terms of the strategic
framework, this example is pretty similar to the game of Kovalenko. In this
position, Black should decide how to counter the threat of Nc6. I have
immediately played} 19... Rdc8 {[%csl Bb8][%cal Ba8b8] Given the fact that in
the future Black is planning to execute the advance ...b6-b5, the b8-square
should be reserved for the other rook.} 20. Qe2 Ne5 {Another important move.
As we have already discussed, in this pawn structure, Black often tries to
provoke the advance b2-b3. In this way, the c3-knight becomes more vulnerable.}
21. b3 {[%csl Bc3][%cal Bb6b5,Bd6d5]} Qb7 {[%csl Bb7][%cal Bb6b5] This is the
perfect spot for the queen. Besides being active, from this position, the
queen also supports the advance ...b6-b5. White decided to radically prevent
Black's idea by playing} 22. a4 {This move, however, makes the queenside even
more vulnerable. Now, Black is already interested in opening the position up
by means of ...d6-d5. Therefore, I played} Rd8 {[%csl Bb3,Ba4][%cal Bd6d5] At
this point, my opponent decided to force the transition into an endgame by
means of} 23. Nf3 Nxf3+ 24. Qxf3 Qxf3 25. gxf3 {[%csl Bf2,Bf3,Be5][%cal Bg7g5,
Bf6d7,Bd7e5] We have the same pawn structure as in the game Marta Bartlel -
Igor Kovalenko. After making sure that the d6-pawn is sufficiently protected,
Black can fix the kingside structure by means of ...g7-g5. Later on, the
knight can be transferred to e5. On the other hand, White does not have any
constructive ideas.} Kf8 26. f4 ({Probably a better idea would have been to
fight for a draw in a rook endgame by playing} 26. Ne4) 26... Ke7 27. Kf1 g5 $1
{From the previous game we know that when White's kingside structure is
compromised. the pawn play is very effective. Besides reducing White's central
control, with my last move, I try to secure the e5-square for the knight.} 28.
fxg5 hxg5 {[%csl Bh2,Be5]} 29. Rd4 Rac8 30. e4 $6 {Positionally speaking, this
move is dubious since it weakens the dark squares on the kingside.} Ng4 {
[%cal Gg4e5]} 31. Kg2 Ne5 32. Rcd1 Rc6 {[%csl Gd6] Now, the d8-rook is free to
operate on the kingside.} 33. h3 Rg8 34. Ne2 Rb8 {[%cal Gb6b5] Reminding White
that the threat of ...b6-b5 is real.} 35. Nc3 Ng6 {Now, the f4-square might
become an issue.} 36. Ne2 b5 $1 {Finally, Black manages to execute this
thematic advance. We can see a classical application of the principle of two
weaknesses.} 37. axb5 axb5 38. Ra1 bxc4 39. Ra7+ Kf6 40. Rxc4 Rxc4 41. bxc4 Rc8
{This move is enough for a winning advantage.} ({Even more precise would have
been} 41... Nh4+ 42. Kh2 Rb2 $19 {when Black is winning on the spot.}) 42. Rd7
Rxc4 43. Rxd6 Rxe4 $19 {Black is winning. Later on, I managed to convert my
advantage.} 44. Ng1 Nh4+ 45. Kf1 Ra4 46. Rd1 Ra3 47. Re1 e5 48. Rb1 Kf5 49. Rd1
f6 50. Rb1 Ng6 51. Ne2 Rxh3 52. Ng3+ Kg4 53. Rb4+ Nf4 54. Rb6 Rh6 55. Ra6 e4
56. Kg1 Kf3 57. Ra3+ Nd3 58. Nf1 Rh4 59. Nh2+ Kf4 60. f3 f5 61. fxe4 fxe4 62.
Ra4 Rh3 63. Nf1 Ne5 64. Nd2 Nf3+ 65. Kg2 Rh2+ 66. Kf1 Nxd2+ 67. Kg1 Nf3+ 68.
Kf1 Kg3 69. Ra2 Rh1+ {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

