{Now, we shall study some examples featuring the advance ...d6-d5. In endgame
positions, this advance is often associated with multiple exchanges and a draw.
Sometimes, however, especially when White's queenside is vulnerable, the
advance ... d6-d5 can be very profitable. This game of Andersson is a perfect
illustration.} 21... Nce4 {[%csl Bc4] Exchanging the c3-knight makes a lot of
sense. Without the knight on c3, it's easier for Black to execute the breaks ..
.d6-d5 and ...b6-b5.} 22. Nxe4 Qxe4 23. Nd2 Qxb1 24. Rxb1 Rc6 {With this
generally useful move, Black anticipates the future opening of the c-file.} ({
The immediate} 24... b5 {would have been possible as well.}) 25. a4 {This
prophylactic move is directed against ...b6-b5. Now, however, the advance ...
d6-d5 becomes more attractive.} d5 26. cxd5 Nxd5 {Andersson is playing
according to the classical principle stating that we should open the position
when there are weaknesses in the camp of our opponent. The next few moves are
quite logical.} 27. Nf3 Bf6 28. Be5 Bxe5 29. Nxe5 Rc2 30. Rec1 Rdc8 31. Rxc2
Rxc2 $17 {Black has a huge advantage in this endgame. Later on, Andersson
managed to win.} 32. Nf3 Kf8 33. Nd4 Rc7 34. Rd1 Ke7 35. Kf1 f6 36. Rd2 e5 37.
Ne2 Ke6 38. e4 Nb4 39. Nc3 Rd7 40. Ke2 Rd6 41. Nd1 Rc6 42. Nc3 Rc8 43. Ke3 h5
44. h4 g5 45. hxg5 fxg5 46. f3 h4 47. Nd5 Nxd5+ 48. Rxd5 Rc4 49. b3 Rc1 50. Rd3
Rb1 51. Kf2 b5 52. axb5 axb5 53. Rc3 Kd6 54. Rd3+ Kc6 55. Rd5 Rxb3 56. Rxe5
Rb2+ 57. Kg1 b4 58. Rxg5 h3 59. gxh3 b3 60. Rg8 Rc2 61. h4 b2 62. Rb8 Kd6 63.
f4 Rc1+ 64. Kg2 b1=Q 65. Rxb1 Rxb1 66. Kg3 Rg1+ 67. Kf3 Ke6 {0-1 Black wins.}
0-1

