{Sometimes in Hedgehog structures, Black accepts a structure with doubled
pawns on e6 and e5. This pawn formation usually arises when White exchanges
his dark-squared bishop for the e5-knight. Let's take a look at one concrete
example. In this position, White played} 19. Bxe5 $1 dxe5 20. c5 $1 {[%csl Bf6,
Bc7,Bb7,Be4,Bf3][%cal Ba7g1] The possibility to execute the advance c4-c5 is
one of the main positional ideas behind Bxe5. White will now try to
effectively use his queenside majority. Nevertheless, if Black manages to open
the position and activate the minor pieces, his counterplay shouldn't be
underestimated.} Rfd8 21. Qe1 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Rd8 23. cxb6 Bxb6 24. Na4 $6 {
Even though the idea of occupying the c5-square seems logical, Black obtains
decent counterplay.} ({More to the point would have been} 24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 25.
Na4 Bc6 26. Nac5 $14 {with a slight advantage.}) 24... Rxd1 25. Qxd1 Bxe4 $1
$132 {This is the point!} 26. Nxb6 Qxb6 27. Nc5 ({In case of} 27. fxe4 $4 Nxe4
$19 {Black is winning.}) 27... Bd5 {[%cal Be5e4] Black has enough counterplay
in view of the potentially vulnerable white king. Black's main idea in this
position is ...e5-e4.} 28. Qa4 (28. Nxa6 e4 $1) 28... g6 (28... h6) 29. Qa5
Qxa5 $2 (29... Qb8) (29... Qd6 $1 $132) 30. bxa5 Bxa2 31. Bxa6 Kg7 32. Nd3 e4
33. Nb4 Bb1 34. Bb5 Bd3 35. Nxd3 exd3 36. Bxd3 Nd5 37. a6 Nc7 38. a7 f5 39. Bb5
g5 40. Bc6 h5 41. Kg1 e5 42. h3 {1-0 (42) Ionescu, C (2465)-Heinbuch,D (2355)
Berlin West 1988} *

