Sometimes, by applying this idea White can force the transition into a
favourable endgame.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 c5 3. g3 e6 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O
Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. b3 O-O 10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. e4 a6 12. Ba3 Nc5 13. e5 {
[%csl Be2] This move forces massive simplifications. In the arising endgame,
White enjoys a slight but lasting pressure.} dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Nxe5 Bxg2
16. Kxg2 {[%csl Bc6] As often happens in the Hedgehog, after the exchange of
the light-squared bishops, Black must take care of the c6-square. Now, the
threat is Nc6 on the next move,} Rdc8 17. Na4 {By using the pin along the
diagonal a3-f8, White keeps creating tactical problems.} Rab8 18. Bxc5 bxc5 ({
In case of} 18... Bxc5 19. Nxc5 Rxc5 20. f4 $14 {White retains his advantage
due to the control of the only open file and the active central knight.}) 19.
Rd3 {White is ready to double his rooks on the d-file. In such positions
White's strategy is based on two elements - control of the d-file and gaining
space on the kingside. Black does not have any counterplay.} Rb7 {[%csl Bh7]
[%cal Bg8f8,Bf8e8,Bf6d7,Bf2f4,Bg3g4,Bg4g5,Bd3h3] After bringing the king to e8,
Black is planning to simplify the position by means of ...Nd7. Meanwhile,
White will try to create another weakness. A possible idea is to fix the
h7-pawn by means of f2-f4 followed by g3-g4-g5, and Rh3. That's the plan that
was chosen by Vaganian in the game.} 20. f4 Kf8 21. g4 Rcc7 ({The immediate} 
21... Ke8 22. g5 Nd7 $2 {does not work tactically -} 23. Nxd7 Rxd7 24. Rxd7
Kxd7 25. Nb6+ {and White is winning.}) 22. Rad1 Ke8 23. Rh3 {[%csl Bh7][%cal
Bg4g5] Already, Black must reckon with the threat of g4-g5.} g6 {[%csl Bh5]}
24. f5 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ba4c3,Bc3d5] By deflecting the e6-pawn, Vaganian wants
to weaken the d5-square.} exf5 25. gxf5 Nh5 26. Re3 {This is a normal human
decision.} ({The computer advocates} 26. fxg6 $1 hxg6 (26... Nf4+ 27. Kf3 Nxh3
28. g7 $18) 27. Rf3 Bg5 28. Rd6 $16 {with a huge advantage.}) 26... Bg5 27.
Ree1 Kf8 28. Kf3 Be7 29. Nc3 Bf6 30. Nd5 Bxe5 31. Rxe5 $16 {Later on, White
managed to convert his huge advantage.} Rc6 32. Ne7 $18 Rcc7 33. Rd8+ Kg7 34.
Nd5 Rc6 35. Re7 Rxe7 36. Nxe7 Rc7 37. Nd5 Rc6 38. Ne7 Rc7 39. Nd5 Rc6 40. Ke4
gxf5+ 41. Kxf5 Re6 42. Ra8 Re2 43. Rxa6 Rxh2 44. Kg4 f6 45. a4 Kg6 46. Ne7+ Kh6
47. Nf5+ Kg6 48. Nh4+ Kh6 49. Nf5+ Kg6 50. Nh4+ Kh6 51. Rc6 Re2 52. Nf5+ Kg6
53. Rxc5 Re4+ 54. Kh3 Nf4+ 55. Kg3 Nh5+ 56. Kg2 Rg4+ 57. Kh2 Rf4 58. a5 Rf2+
59. Kg1 Ra2 60. Nh4+ Kh6 61. Nf5+ Kg6 62. Ne7+ Kh6 63. b4 Nf4 64. Rf5 Ra1+ 65.
Kh2 Nd3 66. Nd5 Kg6 67. Rxf6+ Kg5 68. Rf3 Ne5 69. Rc3 Kg4 70. Kg2 h5 71. Ne3+
Kf4 72. Nc2 Rd1 73. a6 Ng4 74. a7 Rd2+ 75. Kf1 Nh2+ 76. Ke1 Rd8 77. b5 Nf3+ 78.
Rxf3+ Kxf3 79. b6 {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

