{From this game, we start examining the so-called Double Fianchetto. We will
deal mainly with the cases when White avoids Hedgehog positions.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 ({Of course, our move order starts with} 2... b6) 3. Nc3 c5 4. g3 b6 5.
Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. b3 d6 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. e3 {This is the most flexible way
of handling the position. White is planning to proceed with Qe2 followed by
putting the rooks on c1 and d1. He will go for d2-d4 under favourable
circumstances.} ({After} 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 {Black has
nothing to worry about in the arising Hedgehog position. The queen will occupy
the b7-square in order to prepare the advance ...b6-b5. In order to make this
advance easier, Black can also exchange the d4-knight by means of ...Ne5-c6.})
9... O-O 10. Qe2 Qc7 {[%cal Ba7a6,Bf8e8,Ba8c8,Bc7b8,Bb7c6,Bb6b5] Black is
arranging his pieces in a way that is typical for the Hedgehog. After putting
the rooks on e8 and c8, Black can start preparing the advance ...b6-b5. Note
that the advance d2-d4 is almost exclusively met by ...Ne4.} 11. Rfd1 a6 12.
Rac1 Rfe8 13. d4 {Sooner or later, White should go for this advance. From now
on, Black should always be ready for a Benoni type of play arising after d4-d5.
} Ne4 $1 {Remember this thematic idea. By exchanging a pair of knights, Black
is getting ready for a Benoni-type of position.} 14. Nxe4 {White goes for
simplifications.} ({The principled approach would be} 14. d5 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 exd5
16. cxd5 Bf6 $1 {Another typical move. In Benoni structures, due to White's
space advantage, Black is interested in exchanging minor pieces. After} 17.
Bxf6 Nxf6 $132 {[%csl Bf6,Bb7,Bf3,Bg2,Bd5][%cal Bb6b5,Be8e7,Ba8e8,Be3e4] Black
has an excellent counterplay in view of the vulnerable d5-pawn and the
possibility to expand on the queenside with ...b6-b5. If White somehow manages
to play e3-e4, we can always double our rooks along the e-file.}) 14... Bxe4 {
[%cal Bc7b7,Bb6b5] Once the bishop lands on e4, Black has nothing to worry
about. For instance, the Benoni type of play arising after 15.d5 exd5 16.cxd5
Bf6 is even more favourable for Black since his bishop is not stacked on b7.
Meanwhile, we are ready to follow with ...Qb7 and ...b6-b5. White went for
further simplifications by playing} 15. Ne1 Bxg2 16. Nxg2 {[%cal Gd4d5] After
the exchange of the light-squared bishops the move d4-d5 is a threat since
White will be able to take on d5 with the rook. Hence, Black should play} cxd4
17. exd4 {[%cal Gg2e3,Gd4d5] White is playing for a central control. Under
favourable circumstances, he would like to go for Ne3 followed by d4-d5.} ({
The Hedgehog position arising after} 17. Bxd4 Qb7 {[%cal Bb6b5] is favourable
for Black. White cannot prevent the advance ...b6-b5. The following line
illustrates Black's dream scenario in this structure -} 18. Ne1 b5 19. cxb5
axb5 20. Nf3 b4 {[%csl Ba2,Bb3,Be6,Bd6] By fixing White's queenside we are
practically playing with an extra pawn. A possible idea is to play ...d6-d5
followed by ...Bf6. After the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, we can try
to establish a knight on c3.}) 17... Qb7 {[%cal Bd6d5] Executing the advance ..
.d6-d5 is Black's main positional idea in such structures.} 18. Ne3 {The most
natural move. White is preparing d4-d5.} ({A favourable for Black position
arises after} 18. Qd3 d5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ge8d8,Gd7f6] This type of central
tension is favourable for Black. After improving all the pieces, we can
eventually play ...dxc4, thus reaching a favourable version of a position with
hanging pawns. On the other hand, whenever White plays cxd5, the IQP position
will be better for Black.}) 18... Rac8 {Caruana wants to keep the play more
complicated.} ({The simplest solution would have been} 18... d5 19. cxd5 exd5 {
[%csl Bd7,Bb2] with a favourable for Black symmetrical structure. The
b2-bishop is really a problematic piece. If Black manages to exchange his
bishop for the knight as well as all the rooks, he will reach the classical
endgame Saidy - Fischer.}) 19. Ba3 Bf8 20. d5 e5 $132 {[%cal Bg7g6,Bf7f5,Be5e4,
Bd7e5] The complex pawn structure provides both sides with enough resources.
Practically speaking, however, Black's play is easier since his majority is
advancing towards the white king.} 21. h4 g6 22. h5 f5 23. hxg6 hxg6 24. Kg2
Nf6 25. Rh1 Qd7 26. Rh4 Bg7 27. Rch1 g5 28. Rh5 f4 29. Rxg5 fxe3 30. Qxe3 Rf8
31. Rh4 Nh7 32. Rgh5 Nf6 33. Rg5 Nh7 34. Rgh5 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.}
1/2-1/2

