{[%evp 0,83,14,14,23,-3,20,18,18,11,29,40,29,24,23,6,7,13,22,26,25,18,37,36,41,
42,30,0,0,0,0,0,4,0,14,-6,-4,-4,0,0,2,-39,-40,-40,0,-18,-16,-59,-59,-62,-62,
-62,-72,-107,-104,-150,-160,-154,-166,-212,-235,-249,-249,-225,-234,-233,-239,
-233,-242,-233,-148,-138,-127,-126,-121,-124,-123,-157,-151,-157,-157,-179,
-136,-111,-116,-118] This time, MVL plays the setup with Black. Let's see how
he handles the arising Benoni positions.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ({Of course, we
will start with} 2... b6) 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. b3 O-O 8.
Bb2 d6 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 a6 11. Rfd1 Qc7 12. d4 Ne4 $1 {Of course, we never
forget this move in response to d2-d4.} 13. d5 {As we have already pointed out,
this is the most principled continuation. Make sure that you spend the
necessary time on the typical Benoni type of play.} Nxc3 14. Bxc3 exd5 15. cxd5
Bf6 {Another typical move. Having less space, we need to exchange minor pieces.
It's very beneficial that after the exchange of the bishops, our knight will
come to f6, attacking the d5-pawn.} 16. Rac1 Rfe8 17. Nh4 Bxc3 18. Rxc3 Nf6 {
[%csl Bd5][%cal Be8e5,Ba8e8,Bb6b5,Bc7b6] Black achieved his desired setup. Due
to the poor coordination in his camp, White cannot start advancing the central
pawns. At the same time, Black is ready to put pressure on the vulnerable
d5-pawn by playing ...Re5. The following couple of moves are quite natural.}
19. Qd3 b5 20. h3 g6 21. Rcc1 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb5b4] Black is planning
to proceed with ...Ne4 followed by ...b5-b4. The idea is to eventually install
a knight on c3. Obviously, Black has enough counterplay.} ({Even more
promising would have been} 21... Re5 22. e4 Rae8 23. f3 Qd8 $15 {[%cal Bf6h5]
when Black is already better. At any moment, we can use White's vulnerable
kingside with ...Nh5.}) 22. Re1 Ne4 23. Nf3 Qf6 24. Rc2 b4 25. Nh2 Nc3 26. Ng4
Qg7 27. e4 f5 28. Ne3 fxe4 29. Qf1 a5 30. Nc4 Ba6 31. Rd2 a4 32. h4 axb3 33.
axb3 Qf6 34. Bh3 e3 35. fxe3 Qxf1+ 36. Bxf1 Bxc4 37. Bxc4 Re5 38. Rf2 Ne4 39.
Rg2 Kg7 40. Rf1 Rf8 41. Rxf8 Kxf8 42. g4 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

