{The following fragment features a typical strategic mistake that White might
commit in this type of Benoni position.} 19. b4 $6 {White is playing on the
wrong side of the board! Now, the c5-pawn becomes a strong protected passed
pawn!} a5 $1 {The most precise reaction. Black immediately forces his opponent
to clarify the queenside tension.} 20. bxc5 bxc5 21. Qc2 Rab8 22. e4 Bc8 {
[%cal Gc8d7] Activating the most problematic piece in Benoni type of
structures. The bishop is going to d7 from where he will control the entire
board.} 23. Re3 Bd7 {Now, Black is ready to start playing on the b-file. At
the same time, White cannot advance his central pawns.} 24. Qc3 $2 {This move
is already a considerable mistake since it allows Black to invade the
queenside.} Qb6 $1 25. a3 Qb2 $17 {Black has a huge advantage. 1/2 (52)-1/2}
