view. Additionally, it's approved by modern engines!} ({In case of} 7...
Ne4 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. d3 Bb7 10. e4 c5 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 {we get a Hedgehog
type of position that I find slightly passive.}) ({Another very popular option
is} 7... c5 8. e4 d6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Bg2b7,Bc1e3,Bf2f4,Bg3g4,Bg4g5]
Even though Black has enough resources to maintain the balance, a lot of
concrete knowledge is required. White's plans based on Be3 followed by the
advance of the kingside pawns are particularly challenging.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {
[%cal Bc7c5,Bb8c6,Bd8d7,Bf8d8,Ba8c8] This is the first important moment. When
our bishop is already committed to b7, we should recapture on d5 with a knight.
Our perfect setup would include moves such as ...c7-c5 followed by ...Nc6, and
...Qd7. The rooks will occupy the squares d8 and c8.} ({The structure arising
after} 8... exd5 9. d4 {is known to be favourable for White when the black
bishop is on b7. Let's take a brief look at the following sample line -} Nbd7
10. b3 Re8 11. Bb2 Nf8 12. Rc1 c5 13. e3 {[%cal Bd4c5,Bc3e2,Be2f4,Bd1c2,Bc2b1,
Bb1a1,Be1d1] The central tension is obviously in White's favour. White can
always create hanging pawns in Black's camp by playing dxc5. On the other hand,
Black can never release the tension in a favourable way. Of course, before
playing dxc5, White will keep making many useful moves. For instance, the
c3-knight can go to f4 while the rooks will occupy the squares d1 and c1.
Black has nothing better than waiting passively.}) 9. e4 {This is the only way
to pose some problems. White wants to build a strong pawn centre. My
suggestion here is} Nxc3 10. bxc3 c5 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nd7 {[%csl Bc1][%cal
Bc1b2,Bc1f4] We have arrived at the first important position. The most
significant strategic factor is the pawn majorities - White has a central
majority while Black has a queenside majority. If Black manages to neutralize
White's initiative, and his long-term prospects would be quite promising. Also,
both sides will be fighting for control of the c-file. White's dynamic
possibilities are connected with d4-d5. It goes without saying that this move
should be backed up with a very energetic play. Otherwise, White's position
might turn out to be overextended. In this position, White faces a dilemma. He
should decide whether to develop the bishop to b2 or f4.} 13. Bb2 {[%cal Ba8c8,
Bf8e8] This is the most popular choice. The idea is that after d4-d5, the
bishop will be hitting on g7. On the other hand, after d4-d5, Black can
exchange and attack the d5-pawn with ...Nf6. In this case, White does not have
the possibility of d5-d6.} ({In my opinion, even more challenging is} 13. Bf4 {
White is ready to support the march of the d-pawn all the way to d6. Also,
Black is unable to simplify the position by exchanging the dark-squared
bishops.} Rc8 {This move is always useful. First of all, we need to bring all
the pieces into play.} ({The move} 13... Nf6 {would be an inaccuracy in view of
} 14. Ne5 {In general, we avoid playing ...Nf6 when the white knight can jump
to e5. In this position, it's not easy to neutralize White's pressure. A
possible continuation would be} Rc8 15. Qa4 a6 16. Rad1 b5 17. Qb3 {when White
is in full control. The threat of d4-d5 can be very annoying. It's not clear
how Black can obtain counterplay.}) 14. d5 {The most principled and
straightforward continuation.} ({Harmless is} 14. Qd2 {when even} Nf6 {is
possible.} ({Another typical idea is} 14... b5 {trying to occupy the c4-square
by means of ...Nd7-b6-c4.}) {The reason why we allow} 15. Ne5 {is} Nh5 {
since the h5-square is not controlled by the queen. White has nothing better
than} 16. Be3 Nf6 {with a possible repetition.}) ({A typical waiting move in
this position is} 14. Rb1 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd8f6] rulling out any ...Bb4 ideas
before going for d4-d5. In this case, my preference would be} h6 {which is
always a useful waiting move. If White keeps waiting, we can proceed with ...
Re8 followed by ...Bf8, thus taking the steam out of the advance d4-d5. Also,
in some cases, White should also reckon with the advance ...g7-g5.} 15. d5 {
Sooner or later, White should opt for this advance.} ({Another version of the
same idea is} 15. h4 Re8 16. d5 ({The position arising after} 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17.
Bxe5 Bf8 $132 {Remember that when the knights have been exchanged, White's
position loses it's dynamic potential. Most likely, rooks will be exchanged on
the c-file. In the arising endgame, Black outside passed pawn on the queenside
will be an important factor.}) 16... Bc5 {In the setups with Bf4, this is a
very good reaction to d4-d5. Keeping the e-file closed is safer for Black.} ({
The computer claims that} 16... exd5 17. exd5 Bc5 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 {is also
playable for Black. Indeed, if White plays passively, we can put pressure on
d5 by means of ...Nf6 followed by ...Rd8. White's dynamic resources, however,
shouldn't be underestimated. The following computer line shows that the
position is risky for both sides -} 19. Rb2 Nf6 20. Ne5 Rd8 21. Rd2 g5 22. hxg5
hxg5 23. Ng4 Nxg4 24. Qxg4 f6 25. Bxg5 Bc8 26. Qh4 fxg5 27. Qxg5+ Kf7 $11 {
White has nothing better than opting for the perpetual.}) 17. dxe6 Rxe6 {
This move is connected with an elegant exchange sacrifice.} ({The racapture} 
17... fxe6 {usually works well in this pawn structure. Black not only
increases his central control but also opens the f-file for the rook. The
isolated e6-pawn cannot be easily attacked. Had our rook been on f8, the
situation would have been even more advantageous for us.} 18. Qb3 Qe7 19. Rbd1
a5 20. Bh3 {Black enjoys a decent counterplay.} Rcd8 $132) 18. Bh3 Qe8 $1 19.
Bxe6 Qxe6 {In return for the exchange, Black obtained a powerful bishop pair.
Due to his weakened kingside, the absence of the light-squared bishop is a
problem for White. A possible continuation would be} 20. Be3 Bf8 21. Rc1 Rxc1
22. Bxc1 Nc5 $44 {Black has enough counterplay.}) ({A typical idea in such
positions is} 15. Bh3 {By creating an opposition on the diagonal h3-c8, White
wants to add more power to the advance d4-d5.} Rc3 {Invading White's camp and
getting out of the scope of the bishop.} ({Another very strong idea is} 15...
g5 $1 {making use of the advance ...h7-h6.} 16. Bc1 Nf6 {A very energetic move.
Now, White should decide how to deal with the pressure on e4. Our idea is that
after} 17. d5 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 Bxd5 20. Re3 Bc5 $15 {Black has more
than enough compensation for the slight material deficit.}) {Black is
perfectly prepared for the advance} 16. d5 {which will be answered with} exd5
17. exd5 Bc5 $17 {[%cal Gd7f6] followed by ...Nf6. White's position is rather
shaky. It's not clear what the h3-bishop is exactly doing.}) 15... Bc5 $1 {
[%cal Bd7f6] With the rook being on f8, this typical move works even better.
If allowed, Black will play ...Nf6 on the next move.} 16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Qb3 Qe7
$132 {[%csl Be4,Be6][%cal Bf8f1,Bf8f7,Bc8f8,Bg7g5,Bd7f8,Bf8g6] The good
central control as well as the possibility to play on the f-file provide Black
with an excellent counterplay. After doubling the rooks on the f-file, we can
prepare ...g7-g5.}) ({A mistake would be} 14. Ne5 $2 {in view of} Nxe5 15. Bxe5
{[%csl Be7,Bb7,Be5,Bg2] We already know that the positions without knights are
usually harmless for Black. In addition, now Black has a forced way of winning
material.} Bb4 $1 {[%csl Be5][%cal Be1e3,Bf7f6,Bg7g5] A very strong move. The
point is that the e3-square is not available for the rook in view of ...f7-f6
followed by ...g7-g5.} 16. Re2 Ba6 {[%cal Ba6f1,Bb4e1] Suddenly, it turns out
that the white rook has no available squares. After} 17. Rc2 Rxc2 18. Qxc2 f6
19. Bf4 Qxd4 $17 {Black enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 14... exd5 15. exd5 {
[%csl Bd6][%cal Bd5d6] This is the critical position for the evaluation of the
line with 13.Bf4. White is planning to follow with d5-d6. Black has several
decent options, but I managed to find an elegant novelty -} Bb4 $1 $146 {
As we already know, harassing the rook is a typical strategy for Black in this
line. By disturbing the coordination in White's camp, Black will find the
necessary time to arrange his pieces in an optimal way.} 16. Re3 Bc5 {[%csl
Bf2,Bd6][%cal Be3e1,Bd7f6,Bd5d6,Bf6e4] The bishop occupies the stable
c5-square with a tempo!} 17. Rd3 {[%csl Bf6,Bf2][%cal Bd8f6,Bf6a1,Bf6f2,Bf8c8]
The rook belongs behind the passed pawn.} ({After} 17. Re1 Nf6 18. d6 Ne4 $132
{Black is doing fine. White should sacrifice an exchange on e4 and try to
prove compensation afterward.}) 17... h6 $1 {This is the key move you should
know. By taking control of the g5-square, Black prepares ...Qf6. From this
position, the queen controls the entire board.} 18. d6 ({I have also examined} 
18. h4 {rulling out all ...g7-g5 ideas and preparing Bh3. A logical follow-up
would be} Qf6 {[%csl Bd7,Bc5,Bb7,Bf3][%cal Bf8d8,Bb7a6,Bg7g5,Bd7f8,Bf8g6,Bd3d2,
Bc5b4]} 19. Bh3 Rfd8 20. Rc1 Ba6 {Once again, the attacks against the rook are
annoying for White.} 21. Rd2 Bb4 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Rc2 Bc5 $132 {Black is
doing fine. He is ready to initiate new exchanges with ...Nf8. At some point,
the d5-pawn might become vulnerable.}) 18... Qf6 {[%cal Bf8d8,Bg7g5,Bd7e5,
Bb7a6] Black has decent counterplay in this position in view of his active
pieces.}) 13... Rc8 {[%csl Be7][%cal Bd4d5,Be6d5,Be4d5,Be1e7,Bb2g7,Bf8e8,Be7f8,
Bh7h6,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Bb6b5,Bd7b6,Bb6c4] Once again, this is the best move.}
({As usual in this structure,} 13... Nf6 {will be met by} 14. Ne5 {[%csl Bd5]
[%cal Bg2d5,Bd1b3,Ba1d1,Be5c6] followed by Qb3 and Rad1. With a bishop on b2,
this position is even more advantageous for White.}) 14. d5 {[%csl Bb2,Bf4]
[%cal Bd5d6] The most straightforward.} ({Another important idea is} 14. Qb3 {
[%cal Bd4d5] keeping the tension and preparing Rad1. White will try to play
d4-d5 under favourable circumstances. The problem is that in many lines, the
queen is not well placed on b3.} Re8 {[%csl Bb3][%cal Ge7f8] As a rule, when
White does not play d4-d5, we improve our position with ...Re8, ...Bf8, and ...
h7-h6. When the white knight leaves the f3-square, we should consider ...Nf6.}
15. Rad1 Bf8 16. h4 {A thematic idea in this structure. White not only secures
the g5-square for the knight but also prepares to push the pawn all the way to
h6.} ({In this position, Nepomniachtchi played} 16. Bf1 {planning to proceed
with the combination of d4-d5 and Bb5.} a6 {[%cal Bb6b5,Bd7b6,Bb6c4] A typical
idea. Black wants to occupy the c4-square with ...b6-b5 followed by ...Nb6-c4.}
17. a4 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ge7b4] This thematic idea is one of the points behind the
regroupment ...Re8 and ...Bf8. Black wants to exchange the queens via the
b4-square.} 18. Re3 Qb4 19. Nd2 Rc7 20. Ba3 Qxb3 21. Rxb3 Bxa3 22. Rxa3 {
This position was reached in the game ½-½ Nepomniachtchi, I (2705)-Zhao, J  
(2621) FIDE World Cup Baku 2015 (1.2) Now, the simple} Rec8 {[%csl Be4,Bd4]
[%cal Bc7c1,Bg8f8,Bf8e7,Bd7f6] would have provided Black with an advantage in
view of the control of the c-file. Also, White's position is overextended.}) ({
It's important to point out that after} 16. Ba3 Bxa3 17. Qxa3 {Black can
already play} Nf6 {Without dark-squared bishops, the typical} 18. Ne5 {[%csl
Bd4,Bb2][%cal Bd4d5] is less annoying since Black has enough space to maneuver
with his pieces.} Rc7 {[%cal Ba3a7,Bb7e4,Bd8e7,Be8c8] planning to proceed with
...Qe7 followed by ...Rec8.} 19. Qb4 ({In case of} 19. Qxa7 Bxe4 20. Qxb6 Bxg2
21. Kxg2 Qa8+ 22. Kg1 Rec8 $44 {Black has full compensation for the pawn.}) {
This move is always useful.} 19... h6 20. a4 Qe7 21. Qb5 Rec8 $132 {The
control of the c-file and well-placed pieces gives Black an excellent
counterplay. ½- (25) ½ Kragten,J (2322)-Schmalz,P (2222) W-Cup22 WS17 email
ICCF email 2017}) ({One of the main drawbacks behind Qb3 can be seen in the line
} 16. d5 $2 exd5 17. exd5 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Nc5 $17 {when Black is winning the
d5-pawn for free.}) 16... h6 {[%csl Bb3][%cal Bd8e7,Be7b4] This move is always
useful. It's not clear how White is going to improve his position. At the same
time, we have at our disposal the thematic ...Qe7-b4.}) 14... exd5 15. exd5 Nf6
{Black is making use of the fact that with a bishop on b2, White cannot play
d5-d6. It's clear that the d5-pawn will be lost. Therefore, White should play
very energetically in order to prove his compensation.} 16. Nh4 {This is the
right continuation. The knight is heading for the powerful f5-square.} Bxd5 17.
Bxd5 {This move forced the transition into an equal rook endgame.} ({A bit
more tricky is} 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 18. Bxd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5 Rfd8 {In this position,
the rooks are not inferior to White's minor pieces. If Black manages to
exchange the queens, he will be even better.} 20. Qh5 Rc2 $1 {[%cal Be7e2]
Another precise move, introducing the threat of ...Qe2.} 21. Nf5 ({The
position arising after} 21. Bxg7 Rc5 $1 {[%csl Bf5]} 22. Nf5 Rxf5 23. Qxf5 Kxg7
{is equal.}) 21... Qe2 22. Qxe2 Rxe2 $132 {[%cal Bd8d2] with ...Rdd2 to follow.
Black has an excellent counterplay.}) ({After} 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qxd5 Qxd5 19.
Bxd5 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 g6 {only Black can play for a win since a rook and a pawn is
usually stronger than two minor pieces in the endgame.}) {The following
sequence is pretty logical -} 17... Nxd5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nf5+ Kh8 20. Nxe7
Nxe7 21. Qxd8 Rfxd8 22. Rxe7 Kg7 23. Rxa7 Rc2 24. Ra4 Rdd2 $11 {The draw is
obvious.} 25. Rg4+ Kf8 26. Rf4 Rxa2 27. Rxa2 Rxa2 28. Rb4 Ra6 {½-½ Waters,G 
(2381)-Teichmann,C (2426) W-ch34 prel07 email ICCF email 2010} *

