{The last lecture of the camp is dedicated to White's Reti setups without
early c2-c4. The main starting position of the lecture arises after} 1. Nf3 Nf6
2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 {[%cal Ge2e4] This time, we will be mainly
dealing with White's plans based on e2-e4. White is aiming at reaching the
so-called King's Indian Attack. The main suggestion for Black here will be} d5
{[%cal Gb8d7] followed by ...Nbd7. It turns out that Black is perfectly ready
to meet the advance e2-e4 under different move orders. Usually, we will be
getting symmetrical endgames with equal chances. Equality, however, does not
mean a draw. In the annotated model games, you will see how to create winning
chances in all these seemingly equal positions. Therefore, this lecture will
also help you elevate your endgame understanding. At the end of this lecture,
you will find the so-called Odds&Ends section which provides simple solutions
against two tricky move orders - 1.c4 e6 2.Nf3 and 1.c4 e6 2.e4.} ({Ambitious
players are provided with a very decent backup option -} 5... c5 6. e4 d6 {
when Black keeps the structure flexible. It turns out that it's not that easy
for White to find a constructive plan against this setup.}) *

