{[%evp 0,110,31,20,23,3,14,16,11,8,7,27,1,7,6,6,14,4,21,15,16,19,19,15,15,14,
50,49,50,49,64,25,30,-5,-11,-16,8,7,7,8,4,4,23,23,20,22,22,17,25,11,34,22,21,
13,38,8,1,-6,-6,-52,-58,-102,-84,-84,-84,-118,-112,-166,-71,-83,-63,-70,-71,
-55,-69,-71,-74,-72,-81,-75,-70,-70,-67,-500,-503,-511,-516,-519,-494,-494,
-498,-498,-496,-484,-484,-29999,-496,-498,-527,-636,-636,-668,-668,-718,-778,
-903,-1031,-1033,-1161,-1188,-1312,-1416,-1569] At the beginning, I would like
to show my solid variation against the King's Indian Attack. Let's get to the
first important starting position -} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6
5. d3 d5 {I have been using this move order for a long time. I find it very
suitable for QID players. In this position, White has two main directions -
plans with e2-e4 and plans with c2-c4. First of all, we should take a look at
the plans with e2-e4 which are more common in practice. In this lecture, I
will be mainly showing my online blitz games. Let's start with one of them.} 6.
Nbd2 Nbd7 7. e4 {Most of your opponents will go for this move. Black is not
winning a pawn in view of the opposition on the long diagonal.} dxe4 8. Ng5 {
The more common choice. White just wants to regain the pawn.} ({More ambitious
and objectively stronger is} 8. dxe4 {which is the favourite move of the big
KIA expert GM Bassem Amin. White is sacrificing a pawn for the initiative.} e5
$1 {In my opinion, this rare move is the best practical choice. Black is
planning to complete the development with ...Bc5 and ...0-0.} ({After} 8...
Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Qe2 $44 {White has decent compensation for the pawn.}) 9.
a3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2] This logical continuation is the computer's top choice.
White is planning to proceed with b2-b4 followed by Bb2.} ({Another active
move that we need to consider is} 9. Nc4 {putting pressure on e5. In this
position, the simplest way to equality is} Bc5 ({Another interesting
suggestion by the computer is} 9... Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e6] planning to follow with .
..Qe6. Afterward, Black can complete the development by means of ...Bc5
followed by ...0-0-0. You can prefer this fighting option if you are playing
for a win.}) 10. Nfxe5 {This move invites simplifications that lead to full
equality.} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 ({White can also start with} 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Nxe5 {
Nevertheless, after} Nxe4 13. Nd3 O-O $11 {Black has full equality.}) 11...
Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {It turns out that Black can take this pawn regardless of the
fact that his king is still in the centre.} Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Re1 f5 {
Fortunately, this move works quite well. Black makes use of the fact that the
f2-pawn is pinned. The position is already equal. A possible continuation
would be} 15. Bf4 Rd8 16. Nc6 Rd7 17. b4 Be7 18. Nxe7 Rxe7 $11 {The equality
is obvious.}) 9... a5 $1 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g8] An important move in Black's
strategy. The idea is to gain space on the queenside and to secure the
c5-square for the bishop. Black is ready to follow with ...Bc5 and ...0-0. If
White plays passively, he will find himself in a worse position in view of the
superior activity of Black's pieces. The most logical continuation is} 10. Nc4
{when} Bc5 {works fine again. All the variations are identical to the lines
examined above. We can even say that very often the inclusion of the moves
a2-a3 and ...a7-a5 is in Black's favour.} 11. Ncxe5 Nxe5 12. Qxd8+ ({Just like
in the line above, the sequence} 12. Nxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15.
Re1 f5 $11 {leads to equality.}) 12... Rxd8 13. Nxe5 Nxe4 14. Nd3 O-O $11 {
Again, the position is equal.}) 8... Nc5 {It's important to maintain the
control over the e4-square.} 9. Ndxe4 {In more than 90% of your games, White
will opt for massive exchanges on e4.} ({In some games, I have faced} 9. b4 {
So far, I have always answered with 9...h6. When preparing the current file,
however, I have realized that} e3 10. fxe3 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Ncd7 $132 {is even
better. After completing the development with ...Be7 and ...0-0, Black can
strike with ...c7-c5. Black has excellent counterplay in view of White's
overextended queenside and slightly vulnerable king.}) ({White is generally
interested in exchanging all the knights. For instance, after} 9. Ngxe4 Nfxe4
10. dxe4 a5 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] Black is better in view of his superior minor
pieces. He can even consider advancing the h-pawn.}) 9... Nfxe4 {This is the
better capture. Since the c5-knight is more active, I prefer keeping it as
long as possible.} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 {In this position, White has a choice. He can
recapture either with the pawn or with the bishop which is objectively better.
First of all, we will examine} 11. dxe4 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {Even though this
endgame is objectively equal, I will demonstrate how Black can fight for a win.
The passive g2-bishop provides us with some additional chances.} Bc5 {Black
immediately develops the bishop on an active square but fails to anticipate
White's next move.} ({The most precise move would have been} 12... f6 $1 {
planning to answer 13.Bf4 with 13...e5.}) 13. Bf4 Rc8 {Now, as ...e6-e5 is no
longer possible, Black should spend a tempo on this passive move. Nevertheless,
sooner or later, we will manage to play ...f7-f6 followed by ...e6-e5.} 14. a3
a5 {This is the thematic reaction to a2-a3. Securing the c5-bishop is an
important part of our strategy.} 15. b3 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gb3b4] White wants to
prepare the advance b3-b4 by means of c2-c3.} ({The immediate} 15. c3 $2 {
[%cal Gb2b4] would have been a terrible positional mistake in view of} a4 $1 {
fixing the queenside structure.}) {The following couple of moves are quite
logical -} 15... f6 16. c3 e5 17. Bc1 Ke7 18. b4 Bd6 {[%cal Gc8a8,Gb7c6] In my
opinion, Black has decent practical winning chances in this endgame. He is
ready to follow with ...Bc6 and ...Ra8. Our main advantage are the superior
bishops. Both black bishops contribute to the queenside battle. The same
cannot be said about the white bishops.} 19. Be3 Ra8 {[%cal Ba8a7,Bh8a8,Bb4b5,
Bb4a5] The queenside tension is favourable for Black since he can always
release it under favourable circumstances. On the other hand, White should
wait passively since both b4-b5 and bxa5 are huge positional mistakes. Black
is planning to increase the pressure by doubling the rooks on the a-file.} 20.
f3 {[%cal Gg2f1] White wants to bring his light-squared bishop into the game
via f1.} ({It goes without saying that} 20. b5 {will be met by} a4 {[%csl Bb5,
Ba3] fixing the a3-pawn. The b5-pawn can become a target as well.}) 20... Bc6
21. Bf1 Ba4 {[%cal Ba4b3,Bb3f7,Bf1c4] A strong prophylactic move. By
transfering the bishop to the diagonal a2-g8, Black prevents White from
playing Bc4.} 22. Rdc1 Bb3 23. Bb5 Be6 $15 {Black is slightly better. After
doubling the rooks, his plan is to play ...axb4 followed by an invasion on the
a-file. I managed to execute this idea in the game and eventually won.} 24. Bc6
Ra7 25. Kf2 Bd7 26. Bd5 Ra6 27. f4 c6 28. Bc4 b5 29. Be2 Rha8 30. Rab1 axb4 31.
axb4 Ra2 32. Ke1 Be6 33. Rd1 Rc2 {[%cal Ba8a2]} 34. Rbc1 Raa2 35. Rxc2 Rxc2 36.
Rc1 Ra2 37. h4 g6 38. h5 exf4 39. gxf4 g5 40. fxg5 Bg3+ 41. Kf1 Bh3+ 42. Kg1
Rxe2 43. Bc5+ Ke6 44. g6 hxg6 45. hxg6 Rg2+ 46. Kh1 Be5 47. Rg1 Rxg1+ 48. Kxg1
f5 49. exf5+ Bxf5 50. Kf2 Bxc3 51. Ke3 Bxg6 52. Bf8 Kd5 53. Bc5 Kc4 54. Bf8
Bxb4 55. Bg7 Bc3 {GrigorGrigorov won by resignation} 0-1

