{[%evp 0,44,24,15,20,-15,19,16,16,16,16,12,11,2,8,8,-4,8,35,35,27,27,17,14,29,
29,123,29,21,10,50,41,41,17,23,22,33,29,25,24,21,10,16,14,20,14,9] This game
of mine shows what might happen when Black does not play ...e6-e5. The first
12 moves are the same as in the previous game.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7
4. O-O e6 5. d3 d5 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. e4 dxe4 8. Ng5 Nc5 9. Ngxe4 {[%csl Bc5]}
Ncxe4 {This is a slight inaccuracy. Black should have recaptured with the
f6-knight.} 10. Nxe4 ({Given the fact that the f6-knight is not that active,
White could have tried to get a complex position by playing} 10. dxe4) 10...
Nxe4 11. dxe4 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {[%csl Bg2,Be4][%cal Bg2e4]} Bd6 $6 {Once again, I
fail to find the most precise continuation. The last move is designed to
prevent Bf4 but allows the advance e4-e5.} ({Of course, Black should have
played} 12... f6 $1) 13. Be3 $6 {White also does not play in the most precise
way.} ({Of course, the best would have been} 13. e5 Bxg2 14. exd6 Bb7 15. dxc7
$14 {when it's not that easy for Black to regain the pawn without accepting
concessions.}) 13... O-O-O 14. f4 {White is planning to seize space with e4-e5.
} ({The following line shows how easily one can go wrong even in this
symmetrical position. For instance,} 14. Rd2 $2 {would be a mistake in view of}
Bc5 $1 {[%csl Bc7,Bc5][%cal Bb6c5] when White cannot keep his control over the
d-file without spoiling the pawn structure. In case of} 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Bxc5
bxc5 $17 {[%cal Bd8d2] Black has a huge advantage since he controls the only
open file. The threat of ...Rd2 is unstoppable.}) ({If allowed, Black will be
more than happy to fix White's queenside structure. Let's suppose that White
starts fighting for the d-file by playing} 14. Rd3 f6 {[%cal Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Bh7h5,
Bb7c6,Bd6e5,Ba7a5,Ba5a4]} 15. Rad1 g5 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gb7c6,Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gd6e5] An
important move in Black's strategy. The idea is to fix the kingside by means
of ...g5-g4. Black can also start gaining space on the queenside with ...
a7-a5-a4. The bishops will be excellently placed on e5 and c6. The following
cooperative line shows he Black can even increase his advantage.} 16. a3 g4 17.
R3d2 h5 18. h4 Bc6 {[%csl Bc6][%cal Ba7a5,Bd8d7,Bd6e5] Before playing ...Be5,
we will put the rook on d7. We need to exchange only one pair of rooks in
order to restrict White's counterplay. We need the remaining rook to attack
the weaknesses in White's camp.} 19. Kf1 Rhg8 20. Kg1 Rd7 $15 {[%cal Bd6e5,
Bc6d7,Ba7a4,Bg8f8,Bf6f5,Bf5f4] Black is slightly better.}) 14... f5 {This is
the most solid reaction.} ({If Black is ambitious, even better would be} 14...
f6 {[%csl Bg2,Be4][%cal Bg2e4,Be6e5] planning to fix the e4-pawn with ...e6-e5.
The game might continue} 15. a3 e5 16. f5 g5 $1 $15 {[%csl Bc6,Bd6,Be3,Bd4]
[%cal Bf2f5,Bg2e4,Bh7h5,Bb7c6,Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Bc8d7,Bd7e7,Bd6c5,Bd8a8,Ba8a5,Ba5b5]
Remember this strong thematic move. By seizing space on the kingside, we are
ready to start advancing the h-pawn as well. Black can start playing on the
queenside as well. For instance, after bringing the king to e7, we can try to
fix the queenside structure with ...a7-a5-a4. Then White should always reckon
with the maneuver ...Ra8-a5-b5, putting pressure on b2. In some cases, even ...
Bc5 can be considered. After the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, Black
can often install a rook on d4. All in all, Black keeps practical chances to
outplay his opponent.}) 15. e5 Be7 16. Bxb7+ Kxb7 17. Kf2 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rd8 {
Exchanging all the rooks means a draw.} ({More ambitious would have been} 18...
Kc6 $132 {[%cal Ba7a5,Bb6b5,Ba5a4,Ba4a3,Bh7h6,Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Bh6h5,Bh5h4,Bh4h3,
Bh8a8,Ba8a5,Ba5b5] Once again, Black has chances to play on both wings. It
goes without saying that the position is objectively equal.}) 19. Rxd8 Bxd8 20.
c4 Be7 21. Ke2 h5 22. Kd3 g6 {Game drawn by agreement} 1/2-1/2

