{Now, we shall take a look at some examples with light-squared bishops
exchanged.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 d5 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7.
e4 dxe4 8. Ng5 Nc5 9. Ngxe4 Nfxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 {This is the more
solid approach to the position. Nevertheless, as we are going to witness in a
while, Black still has chances to outplay his opponent.} Bxe4 12. dxe4 Qxd1 13.
Rxd1 Bd6 14. Be3 f5 {This break is the simplest solution. Black gains space on
the kingside and challenges White's central superiority.} ({If you are looking
for a more complex struggle, I can suggest} 14... O-O-O 15. Kg2 h5 {[%cal
Gf7f6,Gg7g5,Gg5g4] As always, Black opts for his typical strategy - gaining
space on the wings. After} 16. f4 f5 17. e5 Be7 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7c6,Gh5h4,Gh4h3,
Ga7a5,Ga5a4] , the position is not dead equal. After putting the king on c6,
Black will start gaining space on both wings. Fixing the h2-pawn with ...
h5-h4-h3 followed by the march of the a-pawn is one of our ideas. In order to
reduce White's counterplay, we can exchange one pair of rooks. Of course, with
a correct play, the game should end in a draw.}) 15. exf5 exf5 {[%csl Bd6]
[%cal Be8g8,Bf5f4,Ba8e8,Be8e4]} 16. Rd5 O-O 17. Rad1 Rae8 $11 {[%cal Be8e4,
Be4a4,Bf5f4] The position is equal. Nevertheless, Black still has some
resources. For instance, the advance ...f5-f4 is a bit annoying. Also, Black
can provoke some weaknesses by transferring the rook to the queenside via the
e4-square. Eventually, I managed to win the game.} 18. a4 f4 19. gxf4 Bxf4 20.
Bxf4 Rxf4 21. R5d4 Rf7 22. Rd7 Re1+ 23. Kg2 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 g6 25. Kg3 Kg7 26.
Rd8 a5 {[%cal Bf7f5,Bf5c5,Bg7f6,Bf6e6,Be6d6,Bd6c6,Bc5h5,Bc6c5,Bc5b4]} 27. Rc8
Kf6 28. Kf4 Ke6+ 29. Ke4 Kd7 30. Rh8 Kd6 31. f4 Re7+ 32. Kd3 Kc5 33. c3 Rd7+
34. Kc2 Rf7 35. Kb3 Kd6 36. Ka3 Kd5 37. b4 Kc4 38. bxa5 bxa5 39. Ra8 Rf5 40.
Ra7 Rc5 41. Kb2 Kd3 42. Ra6 Ke4 43. Rf6 Rh5 $19 44. Rc6 Rxh2+ 45. Kb3 Kxf4 46.
Rxc7 g5 47. Rc5 g4 48. Rxa5 g3 49. Ra8 Rh5 50. Rf8+ Rf5 51. Rg8 Rg5 52. Rf8+
Ke3 53. Rf1 g2 54. Ra1 g1=Q 55. Rxg1 Rxg1 56. a5 Kd3 57. a6 Ra1 {
GrigorGrigorov won by resignation} 0-1

