{[%evp 0,46,28,25,30,6,25,15,23,22,22,14,17,2,3,-4,-11,-33,-19,-13,-1,-2,-6,
-11,-9,2,7,-10,-18,-16,-24,-31,-61,-80,-80,-78,-78,10,-63,-120,-120,-141,-172,
-176,-191,-172,-203,-188,-440] In the next couple of examples, we will see how
Black should react when White delays the advance e2-e4. The first encounter
that we are going to examine is the classical game Portisch - Karpov.} 1. Nf3
Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 d5 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. Re1 {The idea of
this logical move is to support the advance e2-e4. On the downside, the
f2-square is now left without protection. Black's most precise continuation is}
Bc5 $1 {This strong move is designed to prevent the immediate e2-e4. In case
White plays passively, Black can proceed with ...0-0 followed by ...e6-e5.} 8.
c4 {In my opinion, with a knight on d2 this move is simply dubious. White does
not really put pressure on d5. On the other hand, his knight will be heavily
restricted by the d5-pawn.} ({The idea behind Black's last move is to answer} 
8. e4 $6 {with} dxe4 9. dxe4 Ng4 $1 {when it turns out that White does not
have comfortable way of defending the f2-pawn. The computer comes up with the
following sequence -} 10. Re2 Nxf2 11. Rxf2 Nf6 12. Kf1 Bxf2 13. Kxf2 Nxe4+ 14.
Kf1 Nd6 $15 {Black's slight material advantage combined with the vulnerable
white king gives us the upper hand.}) 8... O-O 9. cxd5 {White is planning to
follow with Nb3, Bd2, and Rc1. He wants to obtain some play along the c-file.
As we will see, however, the white pieces are not optimally placed.} ({In case
of} 9. d4 {Black's simplest reaction is} Be7 10. b3 c5 ({Another very good
idea is} 10... Bb4 11. Bb2 dxc4 12. bxc4 c5 13. a3 Ba5 {[%cal Ba8c8,Bc5d4,
Ba5d2] Black is ready to proceed with ...cxd4 followed by ...Rc8. If White
plays e2-e3, we will get a favourable version of hanging pawns since White's
minor pieces cannot display any activity.}) 11. cxd5 exd5 {[%csl Bd2,Bc3]
Since the d2-knight cannot put pressure on Black's centre, positions with
hanging pawns are acceptable for Black. Had the white knight been on c3, we
would have avoided this structure.}) ({Of course,} 9. a3 {is always met by} a5
{[%cal Bf8e8,Bd5d4,Be6e5,Bc5f8] Later on, after ...Re8 and ...Bf8, Black can
start expanding in the centre.}) 9... exd5 10. Nb3 Bb4 11. Bd2 a5 $1 {A very
strong move. Black is ready to exchange the dark-squared bishops on his own
terms. After the eventual Bxb4 ...axb4, Black's b4-pawn will provide space
advantage on the queenside. Also, the a8-rook will immediately join the game.}
12. Nbd4 Re8 13. Rc1 c5 {[%cal Bd5d4,Be8e2] Another precise move. Black keeps
gaining space on the queenside. His idea is to put pressure along the e-file
after fixing the e2-pawn by means of ...d5-d4. Black is already better. Karpov
managed to win the game pretty quickly.} 14. Nf5 Nf8 15. d4 Ne4 16. dxc5 Nxd2
17. Nxd2 Qg5 $17 18. Nd6 Bxd2 19. Nxb7 Bxe1 20. Qxe1 Rxe2 21. Qxe2 Qxc1+ 22.
Qf1 Qd2 23. cxb6 Rc8 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

