-436,-438,-861,-403,-522,-478,-1108,-1660,-1567,-2115] In the next examples,
White plays e2-e4 after preparation.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6
5. d3 d5 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. Re1 Bc5 {[%cal Bf8e7,Be8g8,Bf8e8,Be6e5]} 8. h3 {
[%cal Ge2e4] By taking the g4-square under control, White prepares the advance
e2-e4. As we know, the immediate e2-e4 will be answered with 8...dxe4 9.dxe4
Ng4!.} O-O 9. e4 {Finally, White managed to achieve this thematic break.
Black's best reaction is} dxe4 10. dxe4 e5 {[%cal Bf8e8,Bc5f8,Bd7c5] This
symmetrical structure is quite favourable for Black. The most important factor
for the evaluation of the position is the superior activity of the black
pieces. In the next moves, we can increase the pressure on e4 by playing ...
Re8 followed by ...Bf8, and ...Nc5.} 11. Nh4 g6 {By taking the f5-square away
from the white knight, Black is ready to answer Nb3 with ...Be7.} ({In my
opinion, more natural would have been} 11... Re8 {[%cal Bc5f8,Bd7c5] followed
by ...Bf8, and ...Nc5.}) 12. Nb3 {[%cal Gc1h6] chasing the bishop away and
opening the diagonal of the c1-bishop. The problem is that the white knight is
badly placed on b3. Black can harass it by means of ...a7-a5-a4.} ({The
alternative} 12. Nc4 {[%csl Bd8] is well met by} Qe7 {[%cal Be7e6,Be6c4,Be6h3,
Bf8d8,Bc5e7,Bd7c5,Bb7a6] The queen will be excellently placed on e6. Later on,
Black can proceed with ...Rfd8 followed by ...Be7, and ...Nc5. In some cases,
the light-squared bishop can be activated via a6.}) 12... Be7 13. Bh6 Re8 {
[%csl Bb3][%cal Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Bd7c5] White's initiative was only temporary. Now,
he does not have constructive ideas. On the other hand, Black is ready to
continue with ...a7-a5-a4 followed by ...Nc5.} 14. Qe2 Bf8 {It goes without
saying that in this structure, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is
favourable for Black. Therefore, Ponomariov keeps the tension with} 15. Bg5 ({
Of course, after} 15. Bxf8 Nxf8 {[%csl Bg2,Be4][%cal Bd8e7,Bf8e6,Ba7a5,Ba5a4,
Be6c5,Ba8d8] Black is already better. After ...Ne6 and ...Qe7, he will start
advancing the a-pawn. All white pieces are quite problematic in this position.}
) 15... h6 16. Bd2 a5 17. Rad1 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6] A strong move. The queen
is ready to occupy the perfect e6-square. In the next moves, we can see how a
world-class player like Ponomariov is gradually getting outplayed.} 18. a3 Qe6
19. Bc1 a4 20. Nd2 Nc5 21. Kh2 Rad8 $15 {Black is already better in view of
his extra space and more active pieces. Black managed to convert his advantage
into a full point.} 22. Qe3 Kh7 23. f3 Qc6 24. Qc3 Nh5 (24... Rd4 $17) 25. Bf1
Qf6 26. Ng2 Ne6 27. Nc4 Nd4 28. Rd3 c5 29. g4 Ng7 30. Nd2 b5 31. Rde3 c4 32.
Kg3 Nge6 33. h4 Bc5 34. b4 Ba7 35. Qb2 Qg7 36. c3 f5 37. exf5 Nxf5+ 38. gxf5
gxf5+ 39. Kh2 f4 40. Qc2+ Kh8 41. Ne4 fxe3 42. Bxe3 Bxe3 43. Rxe3 Rg8 44. Qf2
