{[%evp 0,78,30,30,30,-20,31,29,22,16,15,12,11,3,-3,-3,-7,-24,-21,-43,-43,-45,
-39,-49,-45,-37,-43,-23,-11,0,-8,-10,-39,-39,-52,-47,-60,-34,-16,-29,-32,-33,
-33,-20,-24,-45,-28,-51,-35,-30,-27,-40,-10,-30,-24,-31,-11,-21,-18,-20,-20,
-20,-20,-20,-18,-28,-31,-37,-24,-135,-151,-151,-133,-179,-115,-220,-206,-234,
-235,-235,-235] The following model game by Eljanov is quite important for
your understanding of the symmetrical structure. The first 11 moves repeat the
previous game.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 Nbd7
7. Re1 Bc5 8. h3 O-O 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 e5 11. Nh4 Re8 {In my opinion. this
is the best continuation. Black makes room for the retreat of the bishop.} 12.
Nb3 Bb4 $1 {I like this move which is designed to spoil White's coordination.
The main point is that after} 13. c3 {the d3-square is getting vulnerable.} ({
Just like in the game Portisch - Karpov, the move} 13. Bd2 {can be answered
with} a5 {Of course, Black wants to exchange the bishops on his own terms.} 14.
a3 ({Of course, the exchange} 14. Bxb4 axb4 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ba8a1,Bc7c5,Bc5c4,
Bd7c5] is favourable for Black. After carrying out the advance ...c7-c5-c4,
Black can increase the pressure by putting his knight on c5.}) 14... Bf8 15.
Bc3 Qe7 $1 {Once again, we see this typical idea. The queen is going to e6.}
16. Qe2 Qe6 17. Rad1 g6 $15 {[%csl Be4][%cal Ba5a4,Bd7c5,Bb7a6,Bf2f3] Black is
already better. The immediate idea is ...a5-a4 followed by ...Nc5. With his
queen being committed to e2, White should always reckon with ...Ba6.}) 13...
Bf8 {[%csl Bc3][%cal Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Bd7c5,Bc2c3] After ...a7-a5-a4 followed by ...
Nc5, Black will be able to make use of the vulnerable d3-square.} 14. Nf5 a5
15. a4 {Remember that the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 is in
Black's favour. The thing is that in the endgame the a4-pawn can potentially
become a target. Therefore, Eljanov forces exchanges by playing} Nc5 {The
following couple of moves are quite logical.} 16. Nxc5 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Bxc5 $15 {
Black is already slightly better. Eljanov managed to win this endgame in a
very instructive way.} 18. Re1 g6 19. Bg5 Re6 20. Nh6+ Kg7 21. Rad1 Rd6 22.
Rxd6 cxd6 23. Bxf6+ Kxf6 24. Ng4+ Ke7 {[%csl Ba7,Ba4,Bc5][%cal Bb7c6,Bb6b5,
Bb2b3,Bc3c4,Be7d7,Bd7c6,Bc6c5,Bc5b4]} 25. Ne3 Bc6 26. b3 Rb8 {[%cal Gb6b5]} 27.
c4 Rf8 28. h4 Kd7 29. Rd1 Kc7 30. Kf1 Bxe3 31. fxe3 Bd7 32. Ke1 Be6 33. Rb1 Kc6
34. b4 axb4 35. Rxb4 Ra8 36. Bf1 Ra5 37. Bd3 Kc5 38. Rb1 Rxa4 39. Kf2 Bxc4 {
0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

