{[%evp 0,82,30,30,25,-6,22,19,15,14,14,9,12,3,7,-6,-18,-11,-8,-14,-13,-13,-12,
-16,-12,-48,3,-47,-41,-56,-33,-52,-54,-66,-40,-12,0,-6,16,-60,-61,-49,-41,-34,
-7,-53,-42,-40,-33,-47,-21,-49,-8,-23,11,25,25,8,9,9,9,9,-4,-4,-4,1,-3,-26,-24,
-27,-24,-24,-49,-49,-21,-79,-39,-58,-87,-53,0,-143,-31,-355,-347] This game
shows how Black should handle the position when White does not fight for the
centre.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 d5 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. Re1
Bc5 {In this position, instead of preparing e2-e4 with h2-h3, White started with
} 8. e3 O-O {Black is ready to grab space in the centre with ...e6-e5.} 9. a3
a5 {Of course, we should always prevent the advance b2-b4.} 10. b3 Re8 11. Bb2
e5 {The most natural continuation. The only drawback is that it allows some
simplifications.} ({Another very good option would be} 11... Bf8 {preparing ...
e6-e5 and freeing the c5-square for the knight.} 12. e4 dxe4 13. dxe4 e5 $132 {
Black is slightly better in this symmetrical structure. This evaluation is
based on the fact that the f8-bishop is superior to the one on g2.}) 12. e4 {
As we know, Black is perfectly ready to play a symmetrical position.} ({
White could have initiated simplifications with} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. d4 Bd6 14.
dxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 $132 {Even though the position is simplified, Black is
still slightly better in view of his space advantage.}) 12... dxe4 13. dxe4 $6
{This is an inaccuracy in view of ...Ng4.} ({White should have gotten rid of
the passive d2-knight by playing} 13. Nxe4 {In this case, Black can play} Nxe4
14. dxe4 Qe7 {[%cal Gb7a6,Ga8d8] followed by ...Rad8 and ...Ba6. Again, Black
can rely on a small advantage in view of the superior activity of his pieces.})
13... Ng4 $1 {This is the problem. White does not have a comfortable way of
defending the f2-pawn.} 14. Re2 Ba6 15. c4 {After this move, Black is better
since White's d-file is very weak.} Qe7 $15 {This move is enough for an
advantage.} ({Another promising direction would have been} 15... b5 {with the
idea to answer} 16. h3 {by means of} Nxf2 17. Rxf2 bxc4 18. bxc4 Qb8 19. Bc3
Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Qb6+ {when White is in trouble in view of his vulnerable king.})
16. h3 Ngf6 17. Qc2 Bb7 18. Nb1 c6 19. Bc3 b5 20. Bb2 bxc4 21. bxc4 Bd6 22. Nh4
g6 23. Nd2 Nc5 24. Nhf3 Nfd7 25. Nf1 Ne6 26. Ne3 c5 27. Nd5 Qd8 28. Qa4 Bxd5
29. cxd5 Nd4 30. Ree1 Nb6 31. Qd1 Qd7 32. Rb1 Nc4 33. Bc1 Rab8 34. Rxb8 Rxb8
35. Bf1 Nb2 36. Bxb2 Rxb2 37. Kg2 Qd8 38. Nd2 Qf6 39. Re3 c4 40. Be2 Bc5 41.
Nxc4 Rxe2 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

