{[%evp 0,42,22,17,22,6,25,26,21,21,11,7,27,29,29,21,21,11,22,-2,-4,-14,-10,-27,
-27,-23,-8,-36,-18,-49,12,-9,-7,-19,44,37,23,23,39,3,23,16,9,12,38]} 1. Nf3 Nf6
2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 c5 6. e4 d6 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Bc2c3,Bd3d4,
Bf8e7,Be8g8,Bb1d2] This is considered the most consistent plan for White.} (7.
Nc3 {[%cal Bf2f4]} Be7 8. Ne1 Nc6 (8... O-O 9. f4 {[%cal Bg3g4,Bg4g5,Bf4f5]})
9. f4 Qd7 {[%cal Be8c8,Bh7h5]}) 7... Be7 8. Re1 O-O 9. c3 {[%csl Bd2][%cal
Bd3d4,Bc5d4,Bc3d4,Bd2b1,Bb1c3]} (9. Nf1 {[%cal Bh2h4,Bf1h2] the most flexible
plan is} Nbd7 (9... Nc6 {is also playable, but optically it looks a bit
dangerous:} 10. h4 b5 11. N3h2 b4 12. Ne3 a5 13. f4 Nd7 14. h5 h6 15. Nhg4 a4)
10. h4 {[%csl Be4]} c4 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc8c1] The point! After the knight
has moved far from c4 this pawn break opens the c-file and weakens d3 for
Black's counterplay.} 11. Ne3 cxd3 12. cxd3 Rc8 $132) 9... Nc6 10. a3 {[%cal
Gd3d4]} (10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 {may run into} Nb4 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Ba8c8,Bb4c2]}
(11... Rc8 12. a3 {transposes to the main line.}) 12. Qb3 (12. Re3 Rc8 $132)
12... d5 13. e5 Ne4 {[%cal Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Ba8c8]} 14. a3 Nc6 15. Qe3 (15. Nxe4
dxe4 16. Rxe4 Na5 $15) 15... Nxd2 16. Bxd2 {Black has a comfortable French as
the g2-bishop cannot participate in a kingside attack.} Na5 (16... Ba6 $5 17.
h4 Na5 {may be a more accurate move order.}) 17. b3 (17. Qd3 $5 Nc4 18. Bc1)
17... Ba6 18. Bb4 Rc8 19. Rec1 Qd7 20. Nd2 $6 (20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. b4 Nc4 22. Qe2
Bb5 23. a4 Bd7 24. Qe1 a5 25. b5 Qb4 $132) 20... Rxc1+ 21. Rxc1 Bxb4 22. axb4
Nc6 23. Nf1 (23. Qc3 Rc8) 23... Nxb4 24. Qd2 Nc6 $17 {Suba,M (2542)-Kovacevic,
S (2383) Villa de Aranjuez 2009 (1-0, 62)}) 10... Rc8 {[%cal Bb6b5]} (10... Ne5
{in my repertoire.} 11. Nxe5 (11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. a4 Rad8 14. Nc4 Ba6
15. f4 Nd7 16. f5 exf5 17. exf5 Rfe8 18. g4 $6 h6 19. a5 Bxc4 20. dxc4 Bh4 21.
Rf1 Nf6 22. axb6 axb6 23. Be3 e4 24. Bf4 Qe7 {David,A (2584)-Marin,M (2552)
Bratto (blitz) 2013 (0-1, 51) My pupils Daniele Vocaturo and Axel Rombaldoni,
who followed this game up close, could not stop exclaiming in admiration after
the game: "But Mikhail, how can you play a blitz game in such a positional
style?"}) 11... dxe5 12. Nc4 Qc7 13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf4 Qc6 15. Qe2 Rad8 16. a4
Ne8 17. Rad1 Qc8 18. Qc2 Nd6 19. Ne3 Rd7 20. h4 Rfd8 21. Ng4 Rf8 22. h5 h6 23.
Qc1 Ne8 24. Rf1 Qd8 25. Ne5 Rd6 26. Qe3 Bg5 {1/2-1/2 (43) Morozevich,A (2716)
-Ivanchuk, V (2711) Moscow 2002}) 11. d4 (11. b4 b5 12. Bb2 (12. d4 a5 13. e5
dxe5 14. dxc5 e4 15. Ng5 e3 16. Rxe3 Nd5 17. Bxd5 Bxg5 18. Bxc6 Bxc6 {with
chances for a dangerous attack.}) 12... a6 (12... a5 $6 13. c4 $1 cxb4 14. cxb5
$36) 13. d4 cxd4 (13... c4 $5 14. Nf1) (13... Nd7 14. Qe2 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nb6 {
is also possible.}) 14. cxd4 d5 15. e5 Ne4 16. Nb3 a5 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. bxc5 f6
19. exf6 Qxf6 {with interesting and unclear play.}) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 b5 {
[%cal Bd8b6,Bb5b4,Ba7a5,Bb7a6] Clearing space for the queen and preparing to
open queenside files.} 13. e5 (13. b3 b4 (13... Qb6 14. Bb2 d5 15. e5 Nd7 16.
Nf1 b4 17. a4 Na5 18. h4 Rc7 19. Ne3 Rfc8 20. h5 $14 {Rodriguez Vila,A (2523)
-Granda Zuniga,J (2601) Buenos Aires 2005 (0-1, 54)}) 14. a4 Na5 15. Bb2 Qb6 {
[%cal Bb7a6,Bc8c7,Bf8c8,Ba6d3,Be4e5,Bf6d5,Bd5c3] Now that things have settled
on the queenside and the c4-square is defended, the queen is welcome on b6.}
16. h4 Ba6 17. Bh3 Rc7 $132 {with mutual chances.}) (13. b4 {runs into} a5)
13... Nd5 14. Ne4 b4 (14... dxe5 15. dxe5 h6 {[%csl Be5][%cal Bd8b6,Bf8d8,
Bb5b4] is simpler. Black has comfortable play.}) 15. Qd3 (15. Bg5 $5 dxe5 16.
Bxe7 (16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxg5 18. axb4 Be7) 16... Ndxe7 17. dxe5 Qb6 18.
Nd6 Rcd8 19. Qc2 Ba8 20. Ng5 Ng6 $132) 15... dxe5 16. dxe5 Nb6 $6 {This offers
White some initiative.} (16... h6 {would at least solve Black's problems.} 17.
h4 Qc7 18. Bd2 Rfd8 $15) 17. Nd6 Rc7 18. Bf4 Nd5 19. Nxb7 Rxb7 20. Bd2 bxa3 21.
bxa3 Qb8 {with reasonable counterplay for Black, Amin, B (2689)-Vachier Lagrave,
M (2789) Riadh 2017 (0-1, 37)} *

