{[%evp 0,58,25,25,15,2,26,22,11,11,18,11,36,10,10,11,11,-10,1,-12,5,-34,-38,
-58,-10,-19,-4,-52,-26,-29,21,32,37,-26,-26,-31,-14,-17,-39,-27,-27,-123,-113,
-114,-127,-140,-132,-136,-128,-306,-312,-381,-418,-418,-532,-581,-654,-773,
-970,-1210,-29988] This is one of my online blitz games in which I applied
our backup option.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 c5 6. Nbd2
d6 7. e4 Nc6 {This move order is slightly less precise.} ({As you can see in
the theoretical file, it's better to start with} 7... Be7 8. Re1 O-O 9. c3 {
Most of your opponents will try to prepare d3-d4 in this way.} ({The idea of
delaying ...Nc6 is that} 9. Nf1 {can be answered with} Nbd7 10. h4 c4 $1 $132 {
In this case, Black opens the c-file and immediately gets sufficient
counterplay.}) {The following sequence is quite typical for the entire
variation -} 9... Nc6 10. a3 Rc8 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 b5 13. e5 dxe5 14. dxe5
Nd5 15. Ne4 h6 {[%csl Bh6,Be5][%cal Bc1g5,Bb5b4,Bd8b6,Bf8d8] Black is already
better. We are ready to follow with simple moves such as ...Qb6 followed by ...
Rfd8, and ...b5-b4. Also, the e5-pawn is quite vulnerable in all these
positions.}) 8. c3 Be7 9. a3 {The idea of this move is to prevent the
combination ...Rc8 and ...Nb4.} Rc8 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. Re1 b5 $1 {
This move is quite typical. Besides freeing the b6-square for the queen, Black
is also ready to strike with ...b5-b4.} 13. h3 Qb6 $15 {Black is already
slightly better. You can take a look at how easily I managed to win this game.}
14. Nb3 Na5 15. Nxa5 Qxa5 {[%csl Be4,Bd4]} 16. Bd2 Qb6 17. Qb1 a5 18. e5 dxe5
19. dxe5 Nd5 20. Bg5 Bc5 21. Rf1 h6 22. Bd2 b4 23. axb4 axb4 24. Qe4 Ne3 25.
Qh4 Nxg2 26. Kxg2 Rfd8 27. Bxh6 Rd3 28. Be3 Bxe3 29. fxe3 Qxe3 {GrigorGrigorov
won by resignation} 0-1

