{The following two examples will provide you with simple solutions against 2
independent move orders that White might try - 1.c4 e6 2.Nf3 and 1.c4 e6 2.e4.
}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.c4 e6 2.Nf3 b6!?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[EventDate "2023.07.14"]

{In this file, we are going to examine the tricky move order arising after} 1.
c4 e6 2. Nf3 {White wants to take us out of our repertoire. Nevertheless, I
will suggest a relatively easy-to-learn system. We should start with} b6 {
We are ready to play in a Queen's Indian style.} ({The main problem with} 2...
Nf6 {is} 3. Nc3 {when we should deal with the threat of e2-e4. We are now out
of our repertoire.}) 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. g3 ({A principled way of handling the
position is} 4. e4 {when we should immediately put pressure on e4 by means of}
Nf6 {Our idea is to provoke White to overextend the centre by playing e4-e5.}
5. Bd3 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gd3e4] This is White's most common choice. By taking the
e4-square under control, White wants to proceed with e4-e5 and Be4 on the next
move.} ({The immediate} 5. e5 {will be answered with} Ne4 {when White has
nothing better than} 6. Nxe4 ({One of Black's ideas is to answer} 6. Bd3 $6 {
with} Ng5 $1 {White's problem is that after the exchanges resulting after} 7.
Be2 Nxf3+ 8. Bxf3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nc6 {The e5-pawn as well as the d4-square tend
to be quite vulnerable. A logical continuation of the game would be} 10. Qe4
Bc5 11. Ne2 f5 $1 {Since Black has better development and superior activity,
it makes perfect sense to open the centre.} 12. exf6 Qxf6 $15 {Black managed
to develop a strong initiative. 0-1 (33) Nogerbek,K (2424)-Mamedyarov,S (2767)
Chess.com INT 2022}) ({In case of} 6. d4 {the simplest reaction would be} Nxc3
7. bxc3 d6 8. Bd3 Nd7 $132 {For sure, Black will emerge with a superior pawn
structure.}) 6... Bxe4 7. Be2 Be7 $132 {Again, Black enjoys a comfortable
position. He will proceed with ...0-0 followed by ...d7-d6.}) ({In case of} 5.
d3 c5 6. g3 d6 7. Bg2 {Besides the usual Hedgehog structures based on ...Be7,
Black can even try the more ambitious} g6 {which was tested by a bunch of very
strong players. After} 8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 O-O 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qe7 $132 {
Black gets a decent version of the Hedgehog. The d6-pawn can always be
defended with ...Rd8 and ...Ne8. At the same time, the bishop is actively
placed on g7. All the typical ideas that we have explained are applicable here.
0-1 (64) Ganguly, S (2589)-Puranik, A (2603) chess24.com INT 2022}) 5... c5 {
[%cal Gb8c6,Gd8b8,Gf6g4] An important move in our setup. If allowed, Black
will start fighting for the central dark squares by means of ...Nc6 followed
by ...Qb8, and even ...Ng4. Therefore, the critical line goes} 6. O-O ({
Less precise is the immediate} 6. e5 {since after} Ng4 7. O-O ({After} 7. h3 $6
Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Qxa8 Nxd3+ 10. Ke2 Ne5 $15 {The weakness of the d4-square
as well as the vulnerable white king provide Black with more than sufficient
compensation for the exchange.}) {Black has the additional option of} 7... Bxf3
({The line} 7... Nc6 8. Be4 Qc8 {[%cal Gf7f5] will just transpose to our main
variation.}) 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Qxa8 Nxd3 $44 {Black has decent compensation for
the exchange.}) 6... Nc6 7. e5 Ng4 8. Be4 Qc8 $1 {An important move that is
also advocated by the computer. By protecting the b7-bishop, we are
threatening the e5-pawn. The game might continue} 9. Re1 f5 10. exf6 Nxf6 11.
d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bc5 14. Qd3 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 O-O $11 {with a
balanced position. 1/2-1/2 (32) Baklanov,V (2408)-Schoen,A (2512) ICCF email
2011}) ({In case of} 4. a3 Nf6 5. d4 Ne4 {we transpose to the line that I have
suggested against the Petrosian System (Take a look at my QID camp).}) 4... Bb4
{This is a very practical and less theoretical solution.} ({We can also play} 
4... Nf6 {transposing to our QID/Hedgehog repertoire.}) 5. Bg2 (5. Qb3 Bxf3 6.
exf3 Nc6 {offers Black great play on the dark squares.}) 5... Bxc3 6. bxc3 (6.
dxc3 {is strategically inconsistent.} Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Bg5 d6 $11) 6... Ne7 {
The start of a flexible regrouping, anticipating White's central expansion.} 7.
O-O O-O 8. d3 (8. a4 Nbc6 9. d3 Na5 10. e4 f5 11. exf5 Nxf5 {, with excellent
play in Pigusov, E (2575)-Ehlvest, J (2625) Novosibirsk 1993 (0-1, 40)}) 8... d6
9. e4 Nd7 10. Re1 e5 11. a4 a5 12. d4 Ng6 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Qc2 Nf6 {Black has
reached a comfortable Nimzo-Indian setup, with all his minor pieces optimally
placed.} 15. Nd2 Qd7 16. f3 Ba6 17. Bf1 h6 18. Bd3 Nh7 $11 {Kasparov,G (2838)
-Kramnik,V (2802) Moscow (rapid) 2001 (1/2-1/2, 42)} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
